\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you give me your full name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 David John Williamson.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 The Shieling, Willougby Avenue, West Mersea, Essex, England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And you're a widower?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you give me the year of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When I - what do you mean, the date when I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ? Yes, the first of August 1908.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And the year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I was born in - on the eighteenth of January 1884.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Whereabouts were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 In Shoreditch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you remember the address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. I can't tell you anything about the address or the place - the kind of p
lace it was - I haven't the slightest idea. When I was a young fellow and first went to work in London with me father he took me for a walk round the streets where I was born. I didn't think much of them 'cos they were - little old narrow - well narrow st
reets and little old houses you know, very old fashioned of course. They were still standing but that's about all. And of course the neighbourhood had deteriorated - it was a slum you might say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know how many years you lived there where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I should think four years because we - I was four years old when we moved to Edmonton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Where did you move to in Edmonton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
A place called The Crescent in Hertford Road. It was a crescent shaped - twenty-five houses in - built in
 a crescent shape in front was lawn - well, close to the houses was a pavement. They were large houses and they were - the pavement in the front of the houses then a roadway with a gate at each end and the crescent shaped lawn in front was about - oh I sh
o
uld think about thirty yards wide or more to the fence in the front and - the - behind the fencing was - there was a dwarf wall with a fence at the front but the actual ground at the - of the crescent, the lawn was about - three foot above the pavement ou
t
side in the main road. And - you could only get access to it by going through the gates at either end - big iron double gates and - the lawn and that was all private property but it was communal, everybody in in the - in the row of houses could use it and
 
- there was a roadway close to the pavement so that - cut - tradesmen's carts could come round and deliver goods and under the pavement were coal cellars. Our house had three coal cellars underneath with a - a round - lid that you lifted up and then the c
o
alman could shoot the coal in and each coal cellar would take about five tons of coal or perhaps more than that and - the - that was private. But eventually the tradesmen were so annoyed at having to come walk through the side - the side gate - a narrow s
i
de entrance - side of the main gates, walking through and knocking at the door and asking whoever it was they were going to deliver goods to to come and open the gates to let them and their cart through or else take the trouble to carry everything through
 
the - narrow gate that - well they - it was blamed onto the tradesmen, the gates was knocked - barged into by some - big - arrangement and knocked the gates down both ends. And - as it was a communal affair they couldn't get sufficient agreement between a
l
l the people to pay their share of - putting up the gate pillars because the pillars were knocked down and the iron gates thrown down. I don't know what happened to the iron gates? I expect they were sold for old iron in the end but they laid there for so
me time until it \endash 
 the row was over and - everybody decided to let the tradesmen drive round. But they were very cagey about the used of the lawn. They wouldn't let - anybody come and park on there or - you know on - on the grass. And the bushes which were 
between - between the railings and the - houses, the bushes, a line of bushes, they were always kept pruned and cared for and the grass was kept moved. And - or cut with a scythe actually. They used to get somebody come and cut it with a scythe and pay a 
t
rifle each. It wasn't - didn't cost much 'cost everybody about a shilling I think for the - grass - 'cos people used to work a lot cheaper than they do now. The grass was cut down with a scythe and kept - tidy. But - then of course the kids that lived the
re they played on the lawn - it was their playground actually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I lived there 'til I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  - 1908 - but my parents lived on there for quite a while - 'til after the - first world war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know why you moved from Shoreditch to Edmonton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well it was to get more accommodation for one thing because my aunt - my mother had a maiden aunt who - had been a lady's companion. to a wealthy lady. And when the lady died the family madder her - her a gift and a -
 small gift and - an annuity - they gave her an annuity to keep - you know - would keep her fairly comfortably and so - she had been living as I say in a first floor - first floor flat for some time where I was taken when my brother was born and - they de
cided to - she decided to join forces and so she had the first floor flat in this house. Had ten rooms the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Two brothers and one sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you give me the order and the spacing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. 
Brother two years after I was born another brother nearly three years after I was born and a sister who was born - well she was eight years younger than I am so she was I suppose born about two years after the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So you were the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Have you any idea how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When I was born he was twenty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know where he came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, he came from Clerkenwell in London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did he do for a living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Watchmaker. Making wa
tches of very high quality. Hand made watches of very high quality which were - capable and where people liked to pay the money for them would were good enough to take a certificate - an A certificate from Kew Observatory for time keeping under all sorts 
o
f conditions of heat - hot - heat and cold and you know they were compensated for heat - and cold and - working in different conditions, you know, different positions - upside down, sideways, any sort of way. See, they were very accurate time keepers. In 
f
act all the watches that we made were guaranteed to go within two minutes a month. To neither gain or lose more than two minutes a month and that - most of them were very much less than that. In ordinary wear, you know, everyday wear under all sorts of co
nditions. They were very expensive watches and they were sold to the large - very large and high rating shops in London in the West End and one in the City.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What would an expensive watch have cost in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well expensive in those days a wa
tch that sold for between thirty and fifty pounds. Gold watch. Of course they were on the way out because - the - government allowed to come into this country watches that were made abroad like - Swiss watches and whereas the English watch, the case had t
o
 be hallmarked - you mustn't sell it for eighteen carat without it was hallmarked and every part of it, the ring that you fix onto your chain and every part of that watch, the inside part of the cases, everywhere had to be the same quality - had to be eig
h
teen carat which was most of those we made. One or two were made twenty-two carat. Of course that was the highest grade in - watches. And - but the Swiss watch could come in marked eighteen carat and the only part was gold - was eighteen carat gold it pro
b
ably the rest of the watch case was gold but it probably much less than nine carat. But just the only part that was eighteen carat the part that carried the hallmark was the part that was snapped into the back of the watch like the glass is snapped into t
h
e front you see. And they were allowed to be sold for eighteen carat gold watch. In - in the shops. Which meant a considerable saving. Pounds in value of the case. And the American Waltam watches that were being sent in their hall mark - every part of the
 
case was the same quality but - inside the case the - the band of the case - the circular part which the hinges upon - where the watch - watch went into that was as - as think as tissue paper with a - built up on a brass - a big solid brass - block that t
h
e watch fitted into. The consequence was when the customer picked up the two watches he could feel the weight - see, oh that's a good solid one, because there was a - half ounce of brass or more in the - in the ring round the watch you see. Well the - the
 handmade English watch had to fight against them for one thing and then - after about 1900 or 1902 everybody wanted wrist watches. And the pocket watch went out of fashion. And died out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your dad have any other job before or after this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 He continued doing that until he retired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 He did that until he retired, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he have any casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. His hours of work precluded everything of that because we used - we living at Edmonton, we used to go up to Lon
don - he used to catch a train - well he went up for - while I was young he went up by train that went at twenty past six every morning and he went up to London. He didn't get home again until half past nine at the earliest - sometimes quarter past ten tr
a
in brought him home, he got home about ten - quarter past ten. Consequently he had no time for any other - jobs or anything else you see, and while we were young we didn't see him from one weekend to the next because he'd gone when we got up in the mornin
g and he wasn't home when we went to bed at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Have you any idea how much he earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember your father ever being - out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. Actually he was foreman of the place where the watches were made. We were about six people worked there. At a bench.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know how old your mother was when you were born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Twenty-seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
She - well she came from - somewhere in London - somewhere quite close handy - trying to think - heard
 her say where she lived - there was a row of houses and - when she was supposed to be in bed me father used to - when he was courting her - he used to come and get over the garden wall and meet with her on the - outside on the - climb up the - the waterp
ipe that come down the top. But anyway - they - where she - where it was it wasn't far away - it was in London, yes, in a row of terraced houses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she have any jobs before she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Oh yes, she did - she worked - she used to make f
ur coats. Yes, you know, sealskin coats and all that sort of thing. But for - they were for the gentry of course but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Have you any idea what firm she worked for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I couldn't tell you the name of it, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she work after she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Have you any idea what hours she worked before she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, I couldn't tell you at all. Fairly long hours but - 'cos I think - I think they were paid piece work more or less and so - they used to work while they had their meals and - as much as they could, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 It was a ten roomed house you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Was ten roomed house, yes, and my aunt had three I should think. Two rooms were side by side with the windows - a balcony in front of the windows - w
ere French windows, you could go out onto the balcony if you wanted to. Then there was another bedroom at - behind them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 That left you with seven rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How many of those would be bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well there was a kitchen downstairs, tw
o kind of reception rooms which eventually me father knocked the wall down between the two so that they could be both - it was used as a very large room if we wanted it - and put folding doors up in place of the wall so that we could open the folding door
s and make one big room. And - get together like see because I - we - had relations - my mother had two sisters who lived not far away and me father had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  sister who lived not far away and - they used to - them and their children used to - come roun
d occasionally. But - we had several friends that we made. So occasionally we used to have plenty of room you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So that left you with four bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I suppose that's what were left. See there was - there was - me father's bedroom and the
n - ours. And - towards the end of the time I was at home my fathers mother came there to live. Of course she was a widow you see and she was getting old, she came and she had a room - one of the rooms upstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have any lodgers besides these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother pay an one to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was the washing done at home or sent out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, all done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother or father mend or make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Me mother used to make our c
lothes but - until we got pretty well on so that we would - didn't want to wear home made clothes then we had a suit bought at the tailors and of course when we went to work we bought our own clothes at - at a tailors in London you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about shoes - did your father ever mend the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Me father used to do all the shoe mending. But of course we bought them at - well mostly they were bought at a place we used to call Mochi's. It was - yes, Mochi's. It was a place in - City Road or a turning o
ff City Road where there was a - a Jewish shop - it was a more or less Jewish quarter around there at the time - and - Mochi is a Jewish name for something that's - not quite - not perfect. Something that's not perfect and this Jews - this - boot - place 
t
his tradesman that used to sell boots and shoes he used to claim that he was selling stuff cheap because there was some slight fault with it. He - very minor faults like the stitching perhaps was out - not straight on them so they weren't perfect but they
 
were quite usable. And so we used to get shoes and things there very, very cheap. And that's where our shoes used to go - come from, I don't know how me father got to know about this place, it's called - it was known colloquially as Mochi's but I forget t
h
e name of the place - its proper name. It had a proper name over the - shop front but it was known as Mochi's because that was the - Yiddish name for something that wasn't quite perfect you see. Oh he didn't make any secret about it you see, he had - he g
ot a - he did sell perfect shoes and boots but you could buy mochi's for - a bit - much cheaper you see. About half the price.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well he didn't have a chance, he was working - he w
as never there. Except Sat - Sundays. 'Cos Saturdays used to work 'til four o'clock and didn't get home 'til five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he do any decorating or repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. All the decorations were done by me father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would he dress or undress or bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
That I couldn't say. I was too young to take notice of that. He may have done, he may not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes he used to read to us. I - I can remember once when I had the measles he used and I had to stop in bed all day as well as al
l night, he - he came in and read to me. When I felt very miserable and howled he sometimes come in and read out of a story book to me. But - I don't remember much about that, not when I was - not me early childhood you see, it was just the same as anybod
y else's and I didn't take particular notice of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would he tell you stories at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh I expect so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well no, he never had the chance much you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Not even Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh Sundays. Well
 Sundays of course - he used to - we used to - before - when I was very young, being the oldest in the family, I used to have to look after the dinner because they - it was the - rule in our house to go to - we - to chapel you see. And they used to go and
 
leave us children at home. And it was my job to see to the cooking because we had a large open range - a large kitchen - a large fireplace and that had got a big fire in the centre with a boiler at the side with a - to make hot water with - a brass tap on
 
it, you could put a bucket under it and draw off hot water. But we had a - what they call a roasting jack, one of these times I'll show it to you, it used to hang up on the mentlepiece, had a hook in it so as you could hang this up then on the roasting ja
c
k you hung - they used to hang always our Sunday joint was a leg of mutton and they used to hang by the - knuckle at that bottom - hang that up on this thing and that went - turned - that was - that would sort of go round and round and round, clonk. Back 
t
he other way, round and round and round, and round - clonk. So backwards and forwards that would go twisting in front of the very hot fire. It was my job to keep putting coal on the fire and keep that burning red hot so that it roasted the meat that hung 
i
n front of it and underneath was a pan that catch - used to catch all the gravy and that that dripped from it. It was my job to have a - I had a big ladle and used to scoop up the gravy and some - leavings, extract of meat me mother used to stir up, and p
o
ur it - you scoop that up and pour it over the meat to keep that from getting shriveled or burnt so as to keep that juicy while that went backwards and forwards. And when they came home you see that was just about cooked. And then a rice pudding had been 
put in the oven - that was about right you see. This - he - my father didn't have anything to do with that you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would your dad look after you if your mother was ever out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well she was never out as I remember - 'course she may have been and i
f - if she was and he was at home he'd look after us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did you have any other tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother or father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well when we - when we got a bit older we used to have to clean the knives and forks because
 they were all the old steel knives and forks, had to be polished - papered up, polished up on what they called a knife board on Saturday. And we had to take that in turns. One Saturday I would have to do the knives and forks and me brother had - me broth
e
r had to do the boots and shoes because they had to be got ready for Sunday. And me father's boots had to be polished as well as our own, 'cos he had to do them himself in the week because of course he'd got them on all the time. And - we used to have to 
c
lean the boots, we did that alternately - take - took it in turns. And then when we got older still so that we could be trusted to go on a journey, one week we'd have to do the knives and forks and boots, the next week we would be sent - on a tram to a pl
a
ce called Silver Street where the shops - where there was the first multiple store - The International set up a - a - International store where you could buy butter and stuff like that cheaper. So we were sent - it was only a penny on the tram to go there
 
and if we liked to walk both ways we could have the penny. Which we mostly did. So my brother - my older - you know, my next brother - my brother that was next to me in age, we used to take it in turns that way. There was one at home doing the boots and k
nives and the other one going up to get the - shopping. We had a big old open basket like the bakers have nowadays to put bread in, you know, a big basket, put your arm through the handle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How long did you go on doing these sort of jobs - after you left school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I can't - really can't say the, you see, the district - grew and shops - one or two shops came about and - I expect the shopping was done nearer at hand. I don't - when I left off going up there I - to Silver Street I can't tell you. A
nd when I left off doing the boots and shoes I can't tell you - probably when I first started work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did you help the younger children with things they found difficult like dressing and eating and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh I couldn't tell you that - n
ot as a regular - it wasn't a regular thing anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you help look after them in any way at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, I don't think - I don't ever remember me mother being out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did the younger children help you at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Not that I know of
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I don't know about certain time - about the same time in - in the early part of the evening you know, we - when we were young we had to go to bed early. We used to - if we talked too lo
ng me father used to come up - shout up the stairs you know. If we weren't quiet he'd come up and - give us a clip of the ear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Not - as soon as we could undress ourselves we had to go to bed our
selves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Any idea what age that would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I haven't any idea, no, not to be able to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
We shared the - I shared the bedroom - one bedroom with the - with my brother next to me for some part of the time but when - how long and when I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you share the same bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. We had separate beds. Because one - when we got older and we were sent to bed early we used to - and me - my brother managed to get hold of a pack of playi
ng cards from somewhere and we used to play nap and under the bedclothes. Someone had given me a - magic lantern for a Christmas present and we used to - it was a paraffin operated thing - we used to light that up so we could shine a light on the cards an
d it didn't show outside the door you see. And as long as we didn't make a noise so - so as me father come up to see what we was up to we was all right so that we didn't always go to sleep as quick as we were supposed to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have a bathroom in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. We - bathed - when we were quite young we bathed in the main kitchen and - used to - one of those galvanized iron baths you see. Used to fill that up with hot water out of that iron boiler that I told you about at the side of the fire wi
th the hot water and pour cold water in to make it right temperature and then we had a large screen that we could put right round the - thing so that we were all shut right off from everybody else you see and then we used to bath and bale the water out of
 
the bath and put fresh in you see for the next comer. But - I don't remember any procession about it - we had on different nights and all that sort of thing to - 'cos we could - it was a very large kitchen - the kitchen was larger than this room. And so w
e
 could - there was plenty of room for us to - be shut off like that and the others were getting on with reading or whatever they were doing you see, it didn't bother. But as soon as we were - really - grown up, me father turned the back kitchen into a kin
d
 of a scullery - there - in the back kitchen there was a copper, old fashioned copper with a big round - arrangement to put water in and a fire under that was - used to be coal fired you see and - an used to have to boil the clothes up in that you see. We
l
l you had to put water in that out of a tap with - with a bucket. Fill that up and empty it with a bucket. Well eventually he - did a bit of rearrangement of the things in there and put a - bath in and knocked a hole through the wall to put the waste from
 
the bath out into the - a rainwater sink outside so that it made it quite a - a cosy bathroom. Because there was an old fashioned fireplace in there and - we used to have a paraffin heater actually - we didn't have - light a fire up in there. Used to have
 a paraffin heater and make that hot enough to - we could bath in comfort in there you see without interfering with anybody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When you were younger do you know how often you had a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Once a week. Sometimes more often if we got dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well usually Sunday mornings. A - a complete change.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 In the main kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were there any occasions when they ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, sometimes 
we used to go up into the big room upstairs, see, put the - the folding doors would be put up and we'd have our - if there was company there we'd have our meals up there. We used to rush up the kitchen stairs with the - big - what they used to call soup t
ureens and vegetables in a big china containers and - they were dished out on plates out of these things put on the centre of the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 In the kitchen downstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 About what time was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well t
hat - I couldn't say. Me father had to have his breakfast very early because he had to catch a train at twenty past six. We didn't see him and the - what time we started our breakfast I couldn't tell you but we used - all used to breakfast together, the c
hildren. Me mother used to sit there and whether she ate - I suppose she had some of the breakfast I couldn't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What sort of things did you usually have to eat for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Porridge. A dish of porridge and a bit of toast usually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Anything to drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, cocoa.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have anything different on certain days such as Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I couldn't say - I don't think we had anything very different for breakfast on Sundays unless me might have had - kippers, you know, divided up. Bit each just to kind of - make a taste on your bread but - never seemed very much anyway, not for breakfast.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would you have a cooked meal midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
We always had something warm for break - for dinner. Sometimes it was what they used to call hash -
 which was meat - meat minced up and seasoned up with some vegetables in it - onions or something, carrots and that. Sometimes we had stew and sometimes we had just meat. But we always had something of that kind - time - you know, right from when we were 
quite young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And you always had the roast on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. That was a sort of regulation affair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about evening meals - did you have tea when you came home from school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 We had tea, yes, when we came home from school or soon afterwar
ds. We had tea and that was very much the same - bread and butter and jam and cocoa or - then when we got older we used - had tea the same as me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have any supper or anything before you went to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, sometimes we had supper. Th
ere again that was - something like - macaroni - or something like - some very - small thing. Until of course, until we went out to work then of course we - when we came home we were like me father, we had a reasonable meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would you have a pudding after dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, usually some rice pudding or some similar thing - sometimes a jam pudding. Were and dig 'em up and shoot them in our basket. He didn't weigh 'em or anything like that. He just put - shoot 'em in with a shovel and two penn'roth - rig
ht oh. You see, you'd get - you'd have so many you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents keep any livestock for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. No. We had a cat usually but - not until we were right grown up me father had a dog but that was something quite extraordinary. Not while we were little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 About how many times a week would you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well I suppose - very nearly every day in some form or other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know if you ever had tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well if we did it would be very seldom. I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever get any extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, no. No. Well I don't know whether there's any poaching available near there. Not when we were - young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family cou
ld have more
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your father have bigger helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well only because he ate more I think, you know, he's - the only thing that he had extra that I know of - as I said, he used to come home - used to have to work 'til four o'clock on Sa
turday and so we'd all had our tea when he came home and it was the custom for me mother to buy a haddock when she went shopping and - and he had this haddock cooked - for his tea. That was always his Saturday tea, you see, he'd been extra long between hi
s
 dinner which he had between twelve and one and so she used to cook him a tea and it was usually a haddock. Ordinary smoked haddock. And we used to keep always somewhere near because times he'd - dish us out with one of the ears or something of that kind 
and although we weren't really hungry it was - sort of special favour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh as far as I know. We weren't made to sit quite - stone silent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or d
id you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well we were issued with our dinner and usually that was whatever was going, you see, meat, potatoes and a bit of cabbage or it was stew it was dished out and that was given to - we were always served alike and - well we usually ate what we wanted of it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well it depended, if they thought you weren't well they - you know - it was all right. They were sorry but - but of course t
hey expected you to give your attention to your meal and not to sit there looking round or dreaming about something else. You were supposed to get on with it and eat your dinner or tea or whatever it was that was put - got for you. Me father was more stri
ct in that way than me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
My mother used to bake bread sometimes but if she did it would be for Sunday's tea - something special, so it was dished up hot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she bottle fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Fruit - I don't know about - yes,
 I suppose she did bottle beans - runner beans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, but we used - on this old kitcheners place, this old range we used to stand on top of the oven a big - one of those big old jam - stone jam jars and we used to get Spanish
 onions and cut them across the - so as to get the rings of onion - flat rings of onion and we used to put them in carefully one on top of the other and - sprinkle in between the layers peppercorns and - cloves and then pour in vinegar and stand it on top
 
of the range where it - it boiled and simmered on and off until they became just right ; pickled you might say. And then we used to have them when we came home from work if we had cold meat or cheese for supper we used to fish out the pickled onions, you 
know, go - nip over there and fetch out two or three rounds you see to give it a - a flavour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she make any wine or medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. I think she made some cough syrup but I can't remember what ingredients there were in that. That 
used to stand on the kitchen range to - get properly incorporated. But it was a very thick syrupy kind of - stuff. A lot of it was that - what they called - Spanish - Spanish licorice they used to call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables or fruit - did you have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - we had a garden but it wasn't a very wide one or very - long. The houses where we lived were part of an estate which were supposed to be for well to-do
 people and - the gardens were - separated by a fairly high wall - about four foot brick wall at the end was separated from the field at the back with a wall that was ten foot high - very high. And - there was a - gate - door which led out onto the field 
a
nd out on that field ware the - which had been stables for carriages for the people that lived in the houses - the stables that belonged to the row of houses so that they could keep their horses stabled out in - and their carriages out there on this field
.
 That was all originally part of the estate but when we - when my father bought the house - only included a share - a communal share on the lawn in front and his own garden. He had no - no share in the roadway - well he did have in a sense a share in the 
roadway at the back so that tradesmen could come and deliver things in the - in the back gate as we called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother buy any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I couldn't say. I don't think so - she used to buy - there was a farm at t
he end of our - at the end of this lane that went along the back called Holt's Farm. The the man's name was Hot or whatever it was, we used to call it Holt's Farm and you could buy two penn'orth of - lettuces as much as you could get your arms round for t
uppence. And - you know, used to go there and buy potatoes, we could - potatoes was about ha'penny a pound. He did 'em up while you waited. Take your basket and he'd dig 'em up and shoot it full and bring 'em home for your mother to cook you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 He didn't make you dig them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh no, he - we never dig - dug 'em up. We used to go with him you see with a basket and he'd walk out from his little - back door onto the place where the potatoes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes. Supposed to sit close to the table and - you know - in a reasonable kind of way, behave reasonably.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Not for meal times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well when everybody had finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How was the meal served when you ate in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well of course it was cooked on the and - or warmed up or whatever was done, on the range and - the table was near enough - there was not a lot - a great deal of space between the - drawn up so that it was - me mother could easily dish up or - or car
ry the dish from the range or the saucepan from the range and put it on the table and that was served in the kitchen only like that. Straight on to our plates from whatever - whatever it was prepared in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When you had your Sunday meal did your dad do t
he carving or did your mum do it all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I don't remember really. I expect it was me father because - carved it - I - I think so, I'm not sure about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you served in any special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Not that I know of. Usually the first on
e served was the furthers away so that you didn't have to pass the plate over the top of other people's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Your dad wasn't served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No I don't think so - not that I know of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Where did your younger brothers and sister sit before they coul
d feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well I think the very youngest would sit next to me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would they have a high chair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And your mother fed them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So they'd be at the table quite young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. Yes, as soon as they
 could sit up, you know, chair - the - original chair part of the - that babies chair - is still about somewhere. I believe my - my son's got it. Yes. It's a little - little copy of one of the old semi circular armchairs only it's miniature so that quite 
a
 young child could sit in it. You know, it was supported on all sides and could be pushed up to the table, there was no room for it to fall out sideways from the - out of the chair. And that was used for us all. I - I expect I - well, it was got for me an
d
 - I sat in it until it was bequeathed to me brother and then went on from him to the next one and to me sister in the end. And then Elsie had - sat in it and - so it's gone on. How I believe my brother's children have been - have gone - have all gone thr
ough it. My son I mean. My son's children. My son's children, they've all gone through it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she show you lots of affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 If you had any worries could you share them with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes. Well its the first person you went to if you got in trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was your father easy to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, of course he did in - you know, in men - you know, usual sort of way, you know,
 he didn't - I suppose we was sat on his knee occasionally to start with when we were little. Oh yes, he made a fuss of us of course but when we got older of course he used - he was very kind to us and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 He wasn't a Victorian father - very stern?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh no, he - he - you had to mind - you had to obey but - he wasn't - he didn't keep you at arms length.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you share your worries with him if you had any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes. Yes, well he used - he'd question you if he thought you was worried about anything. He'd like to know what was going on you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well they expected you to obey, to do what you were told, to be reasonable. You didn't have to say Sir to him or anything like that. Call him dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brother and sister in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes. Yes, because they - they - what - well both me father and mother used to say, was - well if there's any fighting to be done in the house 
we're going to do that, and - so if you - no, no hitting your brothers because if you do well, it will be - you'll be in trouble because if there's any hitting or beating to be done that's - we're the ones to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did they say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, you only - wasn't to - in any way to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - honest, straightforward, truthful and - you know, to work and keep yourself and play a proper part in the world. Helpful part in the world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well yes, they - they - they considered one thing was very important. To recognise the fact that - ultimately you were responsible to God for your life and it should be lived in accordance with the principles of - that he laid down.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well of course they absolutely forbid swearing and wouldn't let us associate with other children if - if they were known to swear in their ordinary conversation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
All depends. If it was nothing to do with us well we just kept quiet or we talked to our - one another you see. We di
dn't interfere with what they were discussing and I expect - I shouldn't be surprised if they didn't discuss anything that was - you know - they were pretty careful what they talked about so that mostly we could take an intelligent interest in what they w
e
re talking about and - if necessary or advise - if it was agreeable we could talk - we could add - join in. We used to live as a family. We were all friendly towards one another and everybody had got an interest in what everybody else was doing or - sayin
g
. Of course as I say my father was - was never very much at home with the children - when - while we were children. And - of course me mother and her aunt used to spend quite a lot of time together, you see, they lived in the same house and - well - very,
 very good friends of course. And so they - we were - we used to play when we were indoors, play with one another - join with one another in what we was doing - reading or - playing games. Card games and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would happen?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well they'd tell you off to start with. And of course if it was something that was really bad you'd be punished for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How would you be punished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 The punish would - the punishment - well it var
ied. If it was me mother administering the punishment like for - for the usual disci - disobedience of young children - there was a - a cane, a thin cane that was hung on a hook on the dresser where the - all the plates and things were stored on the dress
e
r and on one of the hooks was a long thin cane. Well that was used as a last resort. My mother used to usually smack us with an old slipper. A very flat - very thin soled flat slipper and she used to smack us with that because that made a spank - that mad
e
 a good noise, smack, without doing much harm, you know, didn't make any bruises or anything. But - she used to give us a smack with that if we were very naughty and of course if it was something really bad that we'd done, if were found to have - cheated 
or done anything like that or done real mischief then it was reported to me father who used to cane us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How often would you say you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh not very often. We might - might be perhaps two or three times a week with a smack with the slip
per and - a lot of time we used to dodge that because we got a large table in the middle of the kitchen and we used to fly round the table with me mother after us you see. With - with the slipper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember how you felt about being punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I didn't like it. And it certainly had a - an effect on your conduct because - it kept in your memory you see and - it - it came to your aid when you was perhaps preparing to
 do something you got - remembered that it was forbidden and - rather serious to disobey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave room both your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, definitely. They both agreed about that. As I say, me
 father didn't - interfere with - punishment in the ordinary way. Of course if we were at table and we did anything, snatched something belonging to somebody else or anything like that, he'd perhaps clip our ear, you know, give us a cuff at the side of th
e head. But - in cases of real bad disobedience it was reported by mother and - he took the trouble to cane us, you know, to tell us why and make sure that we felt it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well not ex
actly. Not entirely different. We would get a present in the morning when we came down from - came down to breakfast there would be a present at the side of our plate. And - we would have a birthday cake, you know, a cake with sugar on the top and - ornam
e
nted in a way. Well then of course if we were going to have a birthday party which sometimes used to take place well we - the - the majority of the cake was kept to be eaten on that particular occasion. But it were issued with a slice out of it on our bir
thday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 For breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, no, no. Teatime. Breakfast a present - we had a present of some sort you see, it might be - might be some article of clothing, might be a toy, might be anything you see, according to our age and what we were thinking of 
doing you see - or a book. Something there would be for our present - birthday present in recognition of our birthday and we would - everybody would say you know happy birthday and that. Our brothers and sister would say happy birthday and perhaps had a s
weet or two - something like that, their own gift. And - then teatime see, we'd cut the cake - a slice for everybody in the family you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Can you remember anything you did together with your mother and father on Christmas day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 On Christmas Day.
 Oh, we had of course a special - dinner with a Christmas pudding. And after that of course me father and mother used to have a nap - same as all the other folks because my aunts used to - the old - the aunt used to come down from upstairs and - me father
'
s sister used to come round and her husband. And her children. And we used to have a - you know, a special dinner then. The Christmas pudding and - special, mostly a turkey 'cos my uncle was a - salesman in the meat market. Yes, in Smithfield meat market 
m
y uncle. He was a salesman and - so - he used to always buy us a big turkey - big enough for the two families you see and we used to have this cooked - that's from the earliest times I can remember this big turkey was cooked on the Christmas Day and broug
h
t up with a spring of holly on it and that - great fuss made about the - Christmas being Christmas and that and then - we had a Christmas pudding and custard and mince pies, all that sort of thing. And then on - afterwards - after the old people had had a
 
nap, children - of course the children used to keep quiet more or less during that time. They used to play games, you know - used to play games - oh I don't know what they used to call it - all sit round in a circle you know and pass something round, try 
a
nd - somebody standing in the middle trying to - find out where it was you see, yes. All that sort of - all those sort of party games we used to play. I can't remember all of them now but that's one of the games used to be passing something round surrepti
tiously and the one in the middle trying to spot where it was going and catch the one with it - in their possession.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And then you unwrap it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, that's right. And - then there was a - used to have a shuttlecock and all sit round in a circle and 
try and keep it going you see while there's one in the centre trying to grab it. All those sort of games - quite hilarious lots of them were. And then they'd have - one party'd go outside the door into the hall and make up their minds what to do - come in
 
and act some kind of - act a word you see. Charades. The other's would try to guess what it was. All those kind of games we used to play. Pass the time away until it was time for tea. Then we'd have a high tea and after that the Christmas tree had got all
 presents on - used to be - undecorated you know after it had been standing there with the candles alight on it. And the - presents on it shared out and - eventually they all went home - those that didn't belong and we went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you hang up your stockings on Christmas Eve?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes. Oh yes, oh that was the usual procedure to hang your stockings up and then wake up in the morning and find something in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes a vio - violines. We ha
d two violins. One me father used to play and - one I was - taught to play on. But it was a bit of a drawback to me because my sight was always very short - I was always very short sighted. And although me father and mother wouldn't believe it - they made
 
- they thought I was shamming and didn't want to learn to play you see and that was the cause of it saying I couldn't see. Eventually at school - when the school authorities sent round - people to try your sight it was discovered that I really had got sho
r
t sight, you see, and I was provided with a pair of spectacles. But - the violins - my father was quite a good violin player. Then - as time went on and my sister grew up she learned to play the piano and my father bought a piano and - then we used to hav
e quite a - there's a question about that so I won't say any more about that yet. But - yes, there was a - violins in there always you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was there anybody in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Me mother had got a good voice for singing. And in her early
 days - in her young days she belonged to a - group of singers. But I forget the name they were called by. But she'd got a good voice for singing but - you know - there was nobody sing in any - particular way at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, well now that's what I was going to get on to. My sister had this piano and she became quite a good pianoforte player and - she also could play the violin quite well. And - it - of course by the time she was grown up like that we we
re all - grown up and got all manner - many - good many friends. My brothers both joined the Boys Brigade when they were as - age when - eleven or twelve when you can join Boys Brigade and they'd been in the Boys Brigade and graduated up to be - one was -
 
they were both Leiutenants in the Boys Brigade and - course they were attached to a church - a Congregational church and made all - many friends there and - one, one of the - Lieutenant Apted his name was, he was a surveyor by trade and he had been survey
i
ng for the British Government out in the Sahara Desert. Because there's a wonderful oasis out there and - Car - Cargo oasis I think it's called. And he was sent out to try and find more water in the desert see 'cos it's wonderful oasis because there's wel
l
s of water there that never run dry and there's palm trees and all kinds of things that it's a wonderful summer resort. But he was sent out there to survey for the British Government, see if he could find more water and couldn't. Anyway he was a well - ed
u
cated man and - well, a good man. A good leader of men. And - 'course he - he got very friendly with my brothers being associated with them in theirs Boys Brigade and he used to come round, he was a very good piano player and so - my youngest brother, he 
b
ecame a - a fairly good singer, they all used to join together and especially on Sundays we used to get - gang up on Saturdays and Sundays. I - parted with my violin and - bought a cello and my - my - this Apted used to play the piano, I played the cello 
a
nd my sister played the violin and - my brothers and other people that - was got friendly with them used to gang up and they used to - we used to sing. Well on Saturdays all manner of songs. They had a book - I think I've got a copy of it somewhere which 
I
 can show you - it's got all the old songs that have come down through - you might say the ages - all the songs that - comm - comm. - you know, sung in communities. All - all the old favourite songs and we used to sing them at the top of our voices you se
e
 and of course we passed round lemonade and biscuits and all that sort of thing. And that was mostly a Saturday evening. - entertainment - Saturday afternoon my brothers used to play football but I - I like me father had to work very late on Saturdays but
 
Sundays we used to sing hymns. And both Saturdays and Sundays the people out the back - because there was some houses had sprung up out the back on this field that originally had been part of the estate - they used to throw their windows open so as to hea
r
 us singing. We didn't know about it for a long time but - but when they heard us sing - 'cos we - being all crowded in to this room you see always used to shove the window wide open you see so as to get plenty of air in and - you can imagine young fellow
s
 and when they started courting their girl friends used to being there singing at the top of their voices you see. Some'd sing base and that. It was really good. That's how we used to spend our Saturday evening. Of course as - that gradually broke up as f
ar as the Saturdays were concerned because when we started courting - the young people was missing you see, they was out with their girl friends.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, they joined in with all the festivities. When the
y were there - when me father was there he joined in - the same with all these games as I say these - sitting round playing games, they joined in all those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Books? Oh yes. Oh yes, we had loads of books. All Dic
kens works and all that sort of thing and - we were encouraged to join a library. I joined the library in Clerkenwell - the Clerkenwell Library and - the others joined the library when they started a library in - Edmonton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes we used to have a daily newspaper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Any idea which one it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - I don't - I think the Daily Telegraph. Me father had. And - or the Daily Mail, I'm not sure which. And when the Mirror was published we had a Mirror.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have a Sunday paper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, we never had a Sunday paper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have any magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
The only magazine I remember coming into our house was a magazine that was - published many years ago and it's faded out long ago. That was called Alice Sloper. I 
don't know how that was introduced to start with - how it came into our house but that - that was a regular thing, I think it was published on a Saturday but - I'm not sure about that. It was called Alice Sloper, it was a kind of a humorous comic sort of 
thing it was. Sort of a dailym - a weekly comic. Called Alice Sloper. Alice Sloper was one of the characters in it - wore a top hat and got a big nose or something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well only as I say the - mother so
metimes would read to us when we were little children to get us in a good mood for going to bed you see, if we - if you - if you're good and eat up your supper quick I'll let you - read you a little bit more about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know if they ever read aloud to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember a funeral in the family when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Remember what? No, I don't remember. There must have been a funeral because me old aunt - the old aunt died but I - but that was after I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  so I couldn't. I don't remember any funerals in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations when you were a little boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - no. But - about twice I should think I was taken out visiting but that's taken out by the old aunt
 to go and see an old lady friend of hers, a Mrs Cole that lived in Tottenham. She took me up there twice I think but not otherwise, no, they didn't visit much. Didn't have any time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you ever taken shopping? Did you go when you had shoes bought a
nd things like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh we were taken out, yes, taken out to have our shoes bought. For us, fitted on our feet. Things like that of course we were taken out shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Not that I know of. If - if 
it - if I did it'd be - very, very occasionally. See he was always busy at home when once he got in, he - any - any time he got spare he got something on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember any outings with your parents like on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, never. It was unknown.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, had our jobs to do Saturday mornings then we were free, we used to play of course, Saturday morn - Saturday afternoons the sam
e as any other - time when we were home from school while we were young we used to play out on the - field in front of the house. Used to play cricket and - rounders and - hide and seek in the bushes that fronted the place, all that sort of thing. As long
 as we didn't - throw the balls and break any of the windows in the houses we was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did you do on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well Sundays we went, as I say, we - when we were quite young we stayed indoors and then when we were old enough to know what
 we were about we were taken to the - what the - the chapel, if you call it a chapel, in the mornings. And when - the afternoon we went to Sunday school and in the evenings, as soon as we were old enough to stay up late enough we went to the evening meeti
ng. But - otherwise we were put to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have different clothes for Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, we had best clothes to wear - always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Were you allowed to play games on Sunday or did your parents think it wrong to work or play games on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well they - they - they weren't very severe about it but they - they discouraged us from playing games and wouldn't allow us to - do that. What else - what was the other part of the question?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did they think it was wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well it - it - to say it was wrong is a - a - putting it rather too strongly. They thought it was inadvisable and - unbecoming. See that the seventh day was intended to be a day set apart so that you could engage in the worship of God and in recalling
 his - benefits and devote the day more or less to his - honour and service and so - while they didn't - blame anybody for not - for working or blame anybody for playing games and that they - thought it was inadvisable as far as we were concerned because 
we ought to know better you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did both your parents attend a place of worship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Which denomination?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Was called the Christian - what they call them now the Christian Brethren you see. At the time - at that time they wouldn't acce
pt any other term but just Brethren but when the census and that got about and the registration cards had to be filled in and that they had to take some kind of name that was distinctive and so they were called the Christian Brethren - that's what they ac
cepted and that - that's accepted by the Government as a denomination. It's sort of official.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did they both go every Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And when you were old enough you went with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And you went to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes. I used - 'course there were no motor car then, we used to go in what they called a brake - a two horse wagon and all pile into that or perhaps two of them if would be required to carry the children and - g
o out to some place like - Goffs Oak which was then of course a country spot with no buildings or anything of that. And - sometimes to Epping Forest - some part of Epping Forest and - usually it was somewhere where they could - buy tea, you know, buy the 
t
ea and they used to take sandwiches that had been cut up by the - ladies previously and everybody sit round on the grass and - enjoy their tea. And play games - play games to start with then sit down and have a jolly good tea and - a sing-song and more ga
mes after tea until it was coming on - dusk and then - pile into the wagonette and drive home again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Were there any other social activities organised by the chapel that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well sometimes they used to - I've been trying to think of 
what they called it. They would do kind of - play where someone would read a story and the - young people, the women and the - young women and young men would sort of act the scenes and someone - you see they'd act the scenes and in between times that wou
l
d be linked up by reading from a book. And it would be some kind of story with a moral to it you see. Yes, I forget what it was called. No, no. Oh no didn't do anything of Aespos Fables - it was kind of a - a story, like you'd read a story in a story book
 
about a young couple - going on an outing with their children and all that sort of thing. You'd be - some kind of a story weaving in with some kind of adventure in it you see. And so there - there'd be scenes where they'd be all dressed up and - be a very
 
short scene - very short but not much to say in it but just certain actions being done - the curtain was drawn, this went on and the curtains drawn again and a bit more reading done to connect it up with while they got changed ready for the next scene. Ye
s
, sort of - series of tableaux. I forget what it was called but they - they used to do a lot of singing with it you see, get the congregation all singing hymns and that in between times suitable to the - picked out suitable to the story. I forget the plac
e
 that used to publish these things - used to - there was a place that used to publish them so that you could take your pick as to what you did with their - with their suggested - dresses and all the rest of it. Used to occupy best part of an hour you know
. And pass the time away sort of profitably. Interestingly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you belong to a choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Didn't have any choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did the chapel run a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I believe they did for a short time but it wasn't a very - everybody wasn't in favour of it and it gradually dropped out I think. There was nobody very keen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you belong to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, I think I wore a blue ribbon in me lapel of me coat for a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was there a Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, it was - that was included in it you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were there any activities connected with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well they - they had an outing the same as the Sunday School you see, when the - during the summer time they'd have an outing. And perhaps some kind of a get together at Christmas time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you belong to any other club organised by the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Oh yes I did - I belonged to a gymnastic - gymnasium, yes. Gymnasium.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was grace- said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Who said them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Occasionally. But of course with - it was always on the Sunday morning because you see, we - that was the only time then we were all together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - not beyond in giving his vote. He - he was interested I suppose in the political situation, yes, but not to engage in it in any way to - take any part in - getting support for any particular party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well he was what they call a Conservative.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Why do you think he was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well because he believed they were the - they'd got the best ideas - the best programme, the best - most suitable programme for the benefit of the country.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know what her views would be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well she just followed his lead, I don't think she had anything particular - didn't bother about it as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember 
your mother or father voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes, they voted in every general election - every general election - every election there was for a member of Parliament they voted in it. Yes. Well not me mother, I don't think she had a vote did she.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 1918 she would have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh that's - well then she voted for - she voted if she - she was alive, I don't think she was alive when there was any voting for women.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And they would have voted - Conservative?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers - do you know if your father felt himself under that pressure?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, he certainly didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was he a member of a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And he didn't work for one of them at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Nor your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
And they didn't take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. We used to - as children we used to go - go in ban
ds, go along collect all our our own particular friends used to get together and go - in a band going along the street going to school and coming home, we used to come along in a band shouting out you know, vote, vote, vote for Colonel Bowles, who was the
 
can - the Conservative candidate, you see. And that sort of thing. Yes, and - and for Oxford and Cambridge we used to wear the colours or our particular favourite thing and go along the street singing, Oxford is strong, Cambridge is weak, punch him in the
 
belly and make him squeak. And that was put into practice if you could come across a gang of Cambridgeites, you'd try and punch 'em in the belly and make them squeak. So there was few school fights over that. 'Cos they used to feel very much more - clanni
s
h in those days - there was a lot more - strong opinions held and - the schools, the different schools used to fight one another if they met in - you - some of the more militant ones used to organise a gang. Arm themselves with sticks and what they called
 
blood knots which was - a bit of rope worked up into a - big knot at one end and perhaps with a nail or two pushed into it and they used to go and try and find - meet with the other school party and have a fight together. Some of them used to get cuts and
 
bruises and that sort of thing. Very much more clannish in those days than what they are today. Oh yes, oh yes, the Cambridge were just the same as the Oxford - the Cambridge'd go down from school singing Cambridge is strong Oxford is weak, punch him in t
h
e belly and make him squeak. And then some of them would put a couple of boats in the, you know, little wooden - bits of wood with - black - dark blue paint one - sail it down the little stream that used to run down by the side of the - the lane that we w
e
nt up to go to school there was a little stream ran down the side, it goes through a culvert nowadays but used to be an open stream when we used to put a - our Oxford boat on it and these Cambridgeites'd try and stone it and sink it and if they - they - w
e used to try and stone the Cambridge boat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh I don't know, I suppose they really sit in an armchair and have a bit of a breather. Read a book or - or went to sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I couldn't say - she didn't - she had plenty to do inside the home, she had no time to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 She didn't belong to a mothers union or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, there was no mothers union as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, not on her own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Your father didn't get home 'til about ten o'clock most nights did he?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
It was about half past nine when he got home usually at night. Saturdays it was about five o'clock or quarter past five and of course on occasions if he lost that particular train he wouldn't be home 'til quarter past ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well of course he had - he - he was - he slept at home, that's about all. 
Had his supper and went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he attend any clubs or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your father take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I believe the firm that we worked for - he was a foreman of the - this particular works
hop - they had a cricket team, they used to go up and play on - a playing fields, whether there's playing fields at Hyde park is there - anyway it was one of the public parks they used to go and play on for a time, arrange matches with other teams but - i
t
 came to an end because the - man they had that minded the cricket bats and - and stumps and that, took 'em up there - made off with the bats and pawned 'em or sold 'em or something and they - they - that caused the club to peter out. They packed it up. T
h
ey already got fed up with giving their Saturday afternoon or - you see, 'cos they didn't leave off work 'til four o'clock so it had to be, you know, when there was plenty of daylight. They went up and played these matches on the park and got home goodnes
s knows what hour you see. So they were never very keen. That was the only club he belonged to. It was called the Albatross cricket club.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he attend the races at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did he bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Not a boot club or a sick club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Funeral club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Or insurances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh quite well. We - we were very good friends all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. All alike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 As a child who did you play with - your brothers and sister or neighbours?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well we - as I say, we had a nice green out in front that was shut off from the main road and we - our n
eighbours children were all quite - good. There weren't many young children - youngish children then about at the time because the - they were all fairly well to-do people who'd - retired. There was a Naval Captain who was a retired Captain from the Navy,
 
there was a retired Solicitor and - a retired Barrister a retired clergyman, you know, people like that lived along there. And - there were one or two families. We all used to play together, play cricket and rounders and hide and seek in the bushes, it wa
s quite good hide and seek spot 'cos you could - if you liked to push in and out the bushes you could and - they had to stay still and count so many before they opened their eyes you see in that time you might be anywhere.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever play in together childrens homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - yes I did have a - a friend I used to play with but not in his home. The only time I went home with him was the last time I ever did go to his home because his father come home blind drunk and - knocked his sister down. He'd
 got a big sister, who was a big grown up young woman who'd got the tea ready for him - his mother was dead and his big sister used to keep house for the father and the family and - he - we decided to go up and watch the Spurs play at White Hart Lane. And
 
so he lived part of the way out there and so I got permission from my parents to go and have my dinner with him and then go on to see the Spurs play. And - 'cos they - it was in the early days of football, you know, they - very different from what it is n
o
w when everybody goes, swarms and crowds go. Anyway, I went with him and we sat there and played while his sister got the dinner - cooked the dinner and - put it on the table all round - the plates all round the table and presently father came home. Came 
i
nto the kitchen, looked at the table and said, what have you forgotten? So she looked all over the table, she said, I don't know dad, I can't see anything I've forgotten. There's everything there. So he said, well you've forgotten something important - wh
a
t have you forgotten? So she stood there silent for a minute or two and said, I can't see anything dad, nothing. And with that he hit her at the side of the ear and knocked her flat on the floor. And - my pal Harry and me - 'cos we weren't very old - we r
ushed out the house and - I didn't go back any more. So I never - that was the last I had to do with poor old Harry. Never went home with him any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you still stay friends with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes. While he was a school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever go to the parks at all to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Always played on our own ground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And you played cricket and rounders?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, cricket, rounders and - all that sort of games that - that kids can play together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh I suppose we did get dirty playing in the ordinary way. We didn't - make mud pies or anything like that - we were too old for that when we played out there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, within reason, you know, 
they didn't stop us from playing with the other children. With being all shut off from the rest of the road there was - weren't many outsiders came to play with us you see. I don't remember any.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 There weren't any children your parents discouraged you from playing with?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well no, they never seemed to have occasion for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. My brothers, as I say, belonged to the Boys Brigade but I didn't. I was a bit too old I think to - when they started.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
While you were still at school did you have any hobbies - did you collect anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I used to collect foreign coins but of course my scope was very limited being only a schoolboy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 We had some rabbits at one time - pet rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you do any gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, only what we were made to do. We were each allotted a little bit of garden but - and we were all supposed to dig up a stretch at the bottom of the garden so as potatoes could be planted but - th
ere was never any great - incentive to do that because of - you know, the result was not worth mentioning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. The nearest fishing was at Lea - that was some distance away, you know, I never went fishing - I don't think my br
others did either. I - I might say me father had a greenhouse put up and put a grape vine in it. He got a grapevine which he - he grew from a piece he pinched off the grapevine at - what's that famous Kew Gardens. There's a grapevine - a grapevine suppose
d
 to belong to the Queen at Kew Gardens and he nipped a little bit off one day when he was there and stuck it in the ground and it grew and as it grew he put - he eventually put a greenhouse up over it. He built the greenhouse himself over the top of this 
grapevine so that - he got - he used to get quite a good crop of grapes off that. That's only - about the only use we made of the garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you go for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, only when we were courting. Took our girls out for a walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you go bicycling at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, I used to go biking with a school friend at one time. Sunday school friend. A chap named Oliver Gibson. He was a chap that came - came from - Africa. And I met him - he was a Sunday school friend. And - we used to walk about a good de
al but - because when I started courting I was walking out with a girl and left him on the lurch - in the lurch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did you go to any theatres, concerts, music halls or cinemas while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well the most I can remember was ha'penny a week when I was quite young. And we could buy a quarter of a pound of sweets for a farthing. I - I - a place called Binalls and Mother Harrison's
 toffee - toffee. You could buy Mother Harrison's toffee's - an old girl used to make toffee in a big tray. When you went in there for a farthing worth of toffee she used to hit underneath with a - a toffee hammer you know and break a sheet up and then hi
t it with the hammer into small pieces - weigh out a quarter or a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You got that ha'penny every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Ha'penny every week. I got - and then later on that got - went up to tuppence. There was extra penny as I told you we could earn by going - walking to Silver Street and back. And - 'cos I didn't get much more than that when I - 'til I went to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And you spent your pocket money on sweets?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. Always spent it on sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. Only - only the - her aunt used to do some small - I don't think she did much, at any rate only - looking after the children when they were little I expect. Something like that - I couldn't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I couldn't tell you. Probably one of her sisters would come and look after her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
You don't remember what happened when one of your younger brothers or sister was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. No. The only time - part I ca
n remember about that was when my first brother was born. I think it must have been then when I - me mother felt - fainted or collapsed and me father picked her up and took her into the bedroom, put her onto the bed and then booted me out. And - I was kep
t
 shut away until - someone came - mother - might have been one of me aunts and took me to go and live with the old - me mother's old aunt that lived in the flat and I was kept there 'til my brother was big enough for me to go home. Although I don't rememb
er seeing him or anything when I went home again. I was too little to take much notice of what went on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So your parents did have relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes. Oh yes, my mother had - several sisters living within easy reach - all living in London and round about. She had - on, two, three, four - she had four sisters any rate living somewhere near.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How much did you see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh I couldn't tell you. Couldn't tell you. But one of them came to look after her, she'd stop there all the time 'til another sister come of course only occasionally. And we very seldom went to see them but they were there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, loads of friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Where did they see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well at chapel mostly you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So they shared the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Your mother didn't have friends on her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Or your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were your parents friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Their friends? Oh yes, they'd naturally they were free
 to move in and out the same as anybody's friends. They wouldn't have been friends otherwise.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How often would they come in
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well that's difficult to say you see, a youngster don't remember much about the - how often people came in. Be more often 
the young people that'd come in you see - belonging to what you would call the chapel there were quite a number of people of - that we were acquainted with and more or less close friends with that we had confidence in one another you know, that's to say t
h
ere was a kind of a bond between us and naturally their children - or the younger grown ups would feel they were free to come in and - in a place like that where there's - any - in those days there was nothing to attract them anywhere and of course if the
y
 were out for a walk and they hadn't got time to go as far as to - as - for a country walk well it was just natural they should nip in to have a - pass the time of day with their friends. For instance, when - wife and I when we were courting we very often
 
used to call in on our way back from a walk, we used to go out for a walk out to the country - into what was called Meux's Park. That was because there was a very large estate - well I suppose it was about three or four miles away from us, we used to - we
 
were very fond of walking and we used to either get on the - train because we were quite near Edmonton station and - there was a line used to go out - we used to go what they called Theobalds Park, that was two stations - two stations away. And then that 
-
 that was - right at the entrance of Theobalds Park or Meux's Park and it was called Meux's Park because it belonged to - Sir Hedley Meux or some such name as that. Meux was the surname - the breweres you see. Of course they had lots of money and they bou
g
ht this huge place and - in it - there was a place like Temple Bar, one of those gateways you see. Wonderful old gateway to their big house where they lived and - this park of course that extended over acres and acres, I don't know how big it was but it w
a
s tremendous place and of course it was preserved as a country walk. They didn't even like cyclists going through there so as to prevent cyclists going there was a dip in the road, like a hill, you went down a hill and up the other side and - they had - a
 
- cart loads, oh there must have been - goodness knows how many cubic yards of very large stones - stones that measured about - at least an inch to two inches in diameter - these - these huge cart loads were shot down at the dip at the bottom of the dip s
o
 if a cyclist came down the hill he'd got to run in to it you see. And he - off he'd go. You couldn't cycle over it. And although people did cycle because there was a - a action fought I believe to establish a right of way through the park because they wa
n
ted to shut it up entirely - they had gates put there and they were allowed to shut them I think once a year or something, or once every three years, to establish their right of way, you know, to establish that it was their property but there was a proper
 
right of way through it. The public had a right of way to go through there to get to other places you see. And - it was a lovely place. Oh it - at springtime the rhododendrons were a sight to see and - of course they - Lady Meux who was in it - resident t
h
ere at the time - she kept the place, had it kept lovely. So it was a very favourite place for walks, the wife and I used to - when we were courting as I say we used to often go there just go on the railway as far as Theobalds Park and then take a - eveni
n
g walk out there and then when we came back we used to very often - instead of coming on the train back used to walk through the country lanes, through Enfield Town back and call in and see a friend of ours - they were basket makers and had a shop in the 
t
own and - the wife and I were very, very friendly. And that was what your aunt - your grandma would call Auntie May. And - that was Mrs White and your father - grandfather used to you know your auntie - your grandma's husband Will, he used to - he did at 
o
ne time work there for quite a long time basket making. And we - we used to call there practically every Saturday evening through the summertime when we were able to walk so that it was quite use - com - usual to walk about and as I say that it caused you
ng people to visit their relations and friends and of course we had a good many different friends as I say connected with the - chapel. 'Cos - most of them were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  people and had children. Where they - where the children have vanished off to I don't kn
ow - someone we know went to Australia and they didn't all stay in England. All over the place you know, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  and went away to live in different places.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When friends came in would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well if - when - if
 meal time came round of course on a Saturday evening like that they'd be offered lemonade and - biscuits and they'd be welcome to stay to supper if they - were anywhere near late enough. Oh yes they were always welcome and something of that kind was offe
red always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would they come in on any particular days or occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well it would be mostly weekends because it would be the only time they they'd - have any time to spend because the hours of work and the fact that we lived a distance away from 
London where most - nearly all the work was, you see, especially clerical work and things like that, you see, well - they - they were home time to go to bed. See, you - your visits to your lady friend had to be curtailed to about a half - well I was - hal
f an hour - it might be longer than that but you could just call and see her, make sure she was there. And then - that nobody else was cutting you out you see and then you'd - whip off back home to - and - get your own supper and go to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would you 
say that the friends invited into the home were mainly your mother's friends or your father's friends or friends of both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh friends of all of us really. Sort of mutual friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And friends did call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well we were always on good terms with our neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did they pop in and out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I can remember one - set of neighbours that weren't very - that weren't considered welcome but - they were rather doubtfu
l moral character and they soon left. They were only there for quite a short time. But - as children we were not allowed to - well we were warned not to have anything to do with them but all the other people were quite - friendly and - we - as friendly as
 
could be you see, like - two doors from us there was this undesirable person that was in between for a short while, well next door further along was a retired Captain of the Royal Navy. And - of course you had to be very careful that your ball, when you w
a
s playing ball, it didn't go over and bump onto his greenhouse or - go down his area and hit his kitchen windows when you were playing cricket because he'd be after you if you did 'cos he - he was a fiery sort of customer. But he was friendly and he talke
d
 to you and when we got older he was a very fine man to know because he could tell you all sorts of - marvellous real life true stories of adventures because a lot of his time he'd been in charge of a - a Naval ship what the - wasn't as big as a cruiser b
u
t he - it was a - a boat that he was sent out to catching pirates in the China Sea. In the China Seas. And he got lots and lots of things which happened there. Some of them rather - rather thrilling and bit horrifying some because of course if he caught p
i
rates and - he could - it could be established that they were pirates he used to hang them straight away and - destroy the pirate ship but one - on one occasion that he was very sorry and angry about was that - and he reckoned it was a Japanese crew becau
s
e he said they were much more treacherous than the Chinese. And they hailed this boat and fired a shot across the bows and made it stop and then hove to close to it and sent a boats crew - I don't know how many men were in the boat - a boat's crew to go a
n
d go on board and check on the people, you see, and arrest them in the name of the Queen and - see what's to be done about it. Well when their boat drew alongside and - hitched up onto this pirate ship they'd no sooner hitched up and made fast so that the
y
 couldn't drift away - the pirates threw down a sail, an old sail, onto - onto the top of them you see, they were men in the boat preparing to climb up onto the ship and they threw this sail down over the top of 'em and them jumped down on top of the sail
.
 And of course they were immobilised underneath this great old sail and these fellows stabbed them through the cloth - wherever they could feel something moving there they stabbed with their - knives or swords or whatever it was they'd got. Well of course
 
it was a few minutes before he - the Captain - saw what was on foot you see and so he - immediately fired - he'd got all his guns trained on 'em you see, he immediately fired a broadside on to these ship - blew it out the water so to speak but all these -
 
all they - all these other of these pirate people they simply jumped overboard and disappeared - they left the ship. Good many of them got ashore he reckoned. That was what he was sorry for, that any of them got away. 'Cos there's no getting them, they ju
s
t went ashore onto the jungle or bushes or what not and vanished. It was just the same in his work - in - where he was you see. The council put his rates up and he went up and protested and they wouldn't reduce his rates so he stormed out the council cham
b
er and he said, well look, he said, I'll give you - I'll give you a time - about a month, something like that, and if I don't here from you then he said, I'm going to a charge of gun cotton and blow the front out of my house and leave it derelict he said 
a
nd you - and you can get your rates out of that. 'Cos you didn't have to pay rates on an empty house. Made sure nobody else'd go and live in it. If he hadn't had a son and - grown up son living with him very likely he would have done - rather than pay the
 extra rates.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents ever go out and visit friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - they might have done on occasions - they perhaps had an invitation to go on a special occasion, perhaps a - but - there was not much social life in that way you 
know, you didn't - I expect there were people who invited friends to play cards and have a social evening like that but - in our case and our friends you wouldn't do that and so there wasn't - we used to go sometimes and visit them - have tea with them or
 something of that kind and they'd come and have tea with us. The kind of a friendly - get together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements - what do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends or neighbours? Did they make music or play games or sit around and chat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - they mostly sit and chat and - yes, with - if it were only just a social call they wouldn't play any games - they just sit and chat. Later on when my sister grew up and le
arned to play the piano - she might - play the piano for - and sing two or three hymns or something of that kind. But - we'd have been - the larger gatherings like you'd have at Christmas time or - some special - holiday occasion when the - be longer to s
p
end together. But - 'til it developed up I - when I was talking about did I belong to any club I forgot to mention that there was - there was a thing that lasted - it wasn't exactly a club. It was intended to be a musical society. It was got up by two tea
c
hers at the school - the board school. The senior classes - the - the council - started evening classes and among these evening classes were lessons for teaching violin and that sort of thing and my sister was in - interested in playing the violin and cou
l
d play a little and she joined the class for violin playing and the - teacher - the two teachers who were really - organising these special evening classes for music they thought it would be a good idea if they got together a little society for - to play 
m
usic, you know, on their own and so they interested the different students that were learning - violin, piccolo, flute and that sort of things piano and got them together and got them to agree to - join and to learn to play - some things like light opera 
a
nd classical music so as to go through the whole thing and eventually they get - got together a little band of players and then they started out to take on engagements. Like if the church got up a fete like they did - used to in the summer time, get up a 
g
arden fete to raise money for the church the - this little school of - school originated orchestra would go and play music. All - for - well practically all the evening you see, keep on playing so that people could hear the music all the time. And they ha
d
 great ideas about that but it fell through because you see - if you've got a society and they take on an engagement and they're going to play something like the Messiah for instance, or if they're going to play some opera, well, you see, they must be sur
e
 that they've got all the parts and if, like in a - in an organization like that, especially in those days, somebody couldn't get away from work or if somebody happened to be ill and so then the solo violinist perhaps wasn't available, well it would - the
y
 couldn't carry on. So what they had to do - they had to hire somebody. Well then you see, who's going to pay? And they were all - some of them were just - school leavers and very few of them had got jobs where they could afford to pay anything much so th
e
 consequence was that - you see, they got - if they couldn't go it was up to them to pay somebody that could. And if - if they couldn't afford to pay, well then the others had got to foot the bill and there was a bit of moaning about that because teacher 
w
asn't inclined to pay for all the - see, all the absentees. Especially if they got an idea that - those that wasn't very keen'd chuck it up three or four times a month you see. And the consequence was it fell through because they couldn't be sure that the
y
'd get all the people they wanted you see, I - I - I undertook to play the cello in these - performances and I used to have to do a lot of practice you know to make it so that it was worthwhile, I - you had to go what - twice a week to a - band practice t
o
 make sure that you was all together you see. Oh, you see you couldn't do it on scratch, just all come together and just - get your music stuck in front of you and do your best. No, you had to try it over - get so's you could play it properly as well - as
 
well as you could be expected to. And of course I had to cry off several times and I had to pay for somebody to come to play my cello - lend 'em my cello and let them play it, you see. People that belonged to perhaps a theatre orchestra or something like 
that. And could spare the time for - in the afternoon to come and play. So that fell through. That was - of course that was a thing I belonged to but that was the only thing that I can remember that I belonged to except the gymnasium.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Many people divi
de society into different social classes or groups - in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well, in a way yes, but as I said, something to do with their possessions and the money they were able to
 support - to - to - afford on their accommodation. You see, there was Colonel Bowles who was the Member of Parliament, Conservative Member of Parliament for Enfield for many years. Well he was retired Army Colonel but he was a man of - with a considerabl
e
 amount - amount of property. He was - he lived at a place called Forte Hall with tremendous grounds. And then there was Colonel Somerset who also lived in Enfield, he was another man with a lot of money and - he used to drive about with a - what they cal
l
ed a four in hand - four horses and a carriage. Well of course everybody knew that - there's Colonel Somerset coming along and he didn't have to have his postilion that used to ride on the first pair or horses, he didn't have to blow his horn to let peopl
e
 know he was coming. Not very much because, see. Well you see, there were people like that that lived and - carried on with a flourish and - of course they didn't associate and - with the - people that had to work - six days a week. To earn a living. Beca
u
se, well, they didn't think of it and the people that worked six days a week didn't expect them to. Then of course there was a part of Enfield where there were large houses called the Ridgeway where that same sort of - people lived and I can remember one 
p
erson - I've been trying to remember her name - or their name - it was a man as well as a woman. There was a - people that lived there and I'm not sure whether they had a title or not but they were well to-do people that lived in a very large establishmen
t. And - that was - but it was the time when I was engaged to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
 and got - not all our friends knew that we were - about to get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
 in a month or two's time and - of course the date had already been fixed and one of my friends came to me and sai
d, what about - going to live in such and such a house. Now I can't think of the name of the house or the people - why not go and - live there. It's going to be up for sale he says, and I'll - I'll put up half the money he said and you come with me and ha
v
e a look over the place, he said, and it could easily be divided into two - for two families living quite separately and the grounds could be used - well, together would be quite all right. We could help each other keeping the grounds in order. Marvellous
 
place. Looks over so many acres you know and tremendous rooms there, lovely place. So I said to him, well who's going to pay for the coal to keep the rooms warm? I said, you know I said, those - those rooms you're talking of - why they consider a small ro
o
m twenty foot square and I said that's about ten foot high. I said have you ever been in one of those rooms 'cos I said I have. Because being in the watch and clock line I went into some big places at times you see, to - on business for my - employers you
 
see. So - I said, you - you have a try at it before you think of that so I said, I'm right off that. Well now the reason why that place was to be sold was that - the persons daughter had fell in love with their coachman. And eventually, although the famil
y of course - flatly for bade her to have anything to do with him and gave him the sack off straight away as soon as they found it out - the coachman still hung about there and eventually the - they - the young woman run away with him and they got }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 . 
And the family were so shamed at being let down like that - to think that their daughter should have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  a coachman they - and what would their friends think of them - they packed up and went - went away somewhere. Went up north somewhere. Clean out th
e district and wouldn't let anybody know where they'd moved to. Yes. So that was the kind of feeling there was like that you see. But - they'd be friendly enough to speak to you and that sort of thing - they wouldn't treat you as dirt. Then of course ther
e
 were some people who - what you might call the labouring class. Well they - they never had much dance to live in anything like a - a decent place - a - a commodious place but they were respectable people and they were - they were respected as being respe
c
table people. And then of course there were one or two places that became infamous because - gradually they drifted together, birds of a fether flock together they say, drifted together and that was a place that was taboo to all the respectable people. I 
c
an remember one place when I was - as I - a young man and able to take notice - I was courting then because my wife was brave enough to join me in going down this place. It was a place that was known as St Mary's Road. And that was a road - a double row y
o
u know, down each side was a row of small houses with gardens at the back and - these stairs came right down to the street door and they were quite small places and therefore fairly cheap rents compared with the - and there drifted into there a - a lot of
 
people and eventually - a man, if he picked somebody's pocket and he ran away and went down that road which was quite a common occurrence, if he ran down that road he went into one house you could never tell where he might come out because all the back ga
r
den fences were down - at least close to the house so that anybody could go in one house - run right along the garden and most of the back doors was kept open you see so he could - nip in another house and go upstairs and lay up under the roof you know, o
n
 top - nip through the trap door which went up onto the - roof where the water system was you see and - and shut the trap door. Well then it was up to the police to find out which house he was laying doggo in and such was the character of the place that n
o
 policeman would go down by himself. Had to be at least two policemen together to go down there. And no respectable person would go down there you see, would be seen anywhere near there because it was populated by the prostitutes that used to hang round t
h
e pubs, and of course there was no end of pubs in Edmonton and Enfield, there was - I was going to say - well, there was three pubs within - a stones throw - a stones throw distance of where I lived, you see, they were all over the place, public houses. T
h
ese people used to haunt public houses and - it was said that the children there very seldom went to school - even thought the school board officer used to get after 'em occasionally if he dared go down there. And - that they used to get beatings if they 
d
idn't go and steal stuff from the market in Edmonton, you know, what they called the Green where there was a market. If they didn't steal the - steal the stuff to - the vegetables and that to last them over the week - over the week then they - they got a 
g
ood drubbing. Any of the children. Shocking place that was. And - there was a man I knew, he was a Salvation Army Officer and he used to be sent out with a - party of - scouting party as they used to call 'em. Used to go and have an open air meeting and t
h
en march back into the Citadel and if they could get hold of the - bystanders, get 'em along with 'em and come in and have - have - you know, swell their congregation. That was their object - these scouting parties. Well ha al - if he had a scouting party
 
he used to take 'em down this road you see. Well they used to get all sorts of things flung at them but - they - he still kept it up. Finally the Army authorities gave him the sack you know, wouldn't have him for an officer any longer you see because they
 
- he was sidetracking half their congregation perhaps of half their hand anyhow, he got two or three people - one could blow a cornet and another one bang a drum see, so - of course they - they stopped him at that so what he did, he found a house down in 
-
 nearly at the bottom of the road, was empty. And he got onto the landlord and got the landlord to take that - let him take that over. He himself was a - a furniture maker in Bethnal Green at a famous place there - oh - the name's gone from me again - whe
r
e they used to make furniture and he - used to make furniture, that was his business and he - he got a fair income and so he persuaded the landlord, he didn't buy the place but he paid a good rent for it and the landlord allowed him to knock down the wall
 
between the front room and the back room so that he could have it for like a little mission hall. You see. And he held that for - oh, quite a time - I suppose over - over a twelve month anyhow. But eventually the landlord wouldn't let him stop there any l
o
nger because the place was getting knocked to bits because they - they smashed all the front windows and he just boarded them up, he didn't put any more windows and - and they was breaking the place to pieces - they knocked the door off the hinges and all
 
that sort of thing. And - once or twice I used to go down to help support this you see because he had to try and get people to - someone to stand at the door and - all that kind of thing, be at the back of the hall to see what the congregation was getting
 
up to. Because you see he'd tell you if you went down there, well look - oh no, don't you hang your coat up there, you take it up where you - where you can see it. You take it up on the platform and he - keep your eye on it he said. See it was up to the -
 
somebody to see they didn't move out with somebody else's coat or something of that kind you see. And - so he was always in great need of people to be there and my young lady, she was brave enough to come down there. I know one Sunday evening we was going
 
down there and there was a terrific hullabaloo as we was going past a house and - some poor woman come flying down the stairs - she was flung down the stairs from up stairs - flung down the stairs and fell right out in the front garden out the front. Beca
u
se the steps - stairs came right down to the front door, daresay you've seen houses like that, the old fashioned houses in London, you open the door here and the stairs are here and you have to go round that way to go into the - and she come flying down t
he stairs and the door was open. Fell right out into the street - wallop. We didn't dare go and pick her up. There was a terrific hullabaloo going on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Which class would you say you yourself belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well we was the - sort of working class. T
hat's to say we had to go - we was away six days a week at work. We used to - you see the trains up to Liverpool Street - you could go from Edmonton to Liverpool Street for tuppence a day - return fare. Tuppence return fare - if you went early enough. And
 
used, you see, the trains used to start at - well - they were sixpence I think at four o'clock. They used to start at four o'clock for the market people - people that went to market at Smithfield and Billingsgate you see. They started about four o'clock t
h
e trains well then they were about sixpence up 'til about five or soon after five - about five or five - st twenty they were tuppence. And you could catch five twenty, the five fifty-five, the six ten the six twenty or six fifteen or I don't know whether 
i
ts six twenty, six fifteen - anyhow, then there was the six forty-five, six fifty-five you see and then there'd come again the - about - they was threepence just before seven 'til about ten past seven then they went up and the full - full day fare - after
 
about half past eight was one and a penny. Well of course there was such rows about the overcrowding on these tuppence trains - the later tuppeny trains that the railway company got annoyed with the constant representations made to them by the local counc
i
ls, by the - various social - clubs and communities about the people obliged to travel twenty in a compartment - compartment meant to take twelve you see - standing up on one another's toes and all the rest of it - unhealthy and bad. And so they said well
 
look, we'll only issue tickets to - that the train shall be reasonably full. And so you see you could only get a ticket for a train that had got accommodation for you. Well, that didn't last long for the simple reason that the people that had to get to wo
r
k latish like the clerks and whatnot, they were - they were the people that got home latest you see, the people that went to work in the market, they got home earlier so they could get the tickets for the later trains you see - they'd want a ticket for th
e
 six - for the seven ten you see or the seven fifteen. Well they was the ones that was sold first and the - the poor devils that had to - like the poor girls that worked in the factories where they didn't start work 'til eight o'clock or half past eight, 
t
hey'd got to have tickets to get - at six o'clock you see. And so they was up in London by half past six - quarter to seven and got to wait 'til eight o'clock before they could get into work. Well that was they going to do in the winter time. Nowhere they
 
could go you see. So - finally there was such a racket and a riot about it - a lot of people - rushed the later trains with their tuppeny tickets - rushed the later trains and - rushed the barriers at Liverpool Street and caused such a commotion and it wa
s
 taken up by some clergyman up in London who'd been making his church available for girls that got up there at half past six and go in the church and some - philanthropic ladies made tea and coffee and sold it to 'em for about ha'penny a cup or something 
l
ike that you see. So they got something - somewhere where they could sit and it - well, it was anyway out of the elements, it wasn't pouring with rain in there you see they - and he took it up and finally the - train authorities they ran enough trains by 
u
sing what was called the low level line - that used to run through the Green and people could buy a ticket for threepence provided the bought tickets of - every - a weeks tickets at a time and they were people that were of a working class - that is to say
 
they weren't top of working in a stockbrokers office, he wouldn't be able to get a threepenny ticket, he'd have to pay his one and a penny. But the other people could go at a reasonable time - in there - there was quite some riots - really real riots at t
i
mes. 'Cos of course the people that went up and - that forced their way through and rushed the barriers at Liverpool Street they didn't go home by train because the return half of their ticket would have given them away you see. So - so what they did - th
ey went home by tram and all that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What sort of people belonged to the same group as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well they - I - I suppose the people that I used to know that - well see what did they work at. There's one chap I used to know he was a
 - he used to make - all kinds of metal wear like the things they used to - the coppers that they used to used in the old brick coppers for boiling all kinds of things in like that. Bit - what they used to call steam kettles, you know, big kettles that th
e
y used to cook in the - in the restaurants, in the caterers used to use. He used to - and he used to be sit sitting on a - on a stool hammering and banging, well he'd got an anvil you see, and banging these things up into shape. And making - shaping them 
u
p - making all kinds of things like that. Well that was his job. And then - see what - another chap I used to know, he made packing cases for Tommy Lipton's the - making packing cases to take their big consignments of groceries you see which they used to 
s
end out - tea and all that sort of stuff. On their vans you see, they had vans running all over London and - and delivering things at one time - Tommy Liptons. They - he used to work there making these packing cases 'til he got all the fingers sawed off h
i
s left hand on a circular saw - cutting. But he got compensation for that. Yes he got compensation - enough to - to buy a little grocers shop in Woolwich. It was a corner shop and - looked a very desirable place but when he got in there he found he got no
 
customers, although there were swarms of people living round him. But what he did get, every night he got a gang of rough lads used to come - what they called the belt and buckle boys - used to come there and push one another about and anybody that went b
y
 used to get pushed out in the road, you see, they'd push - push one'd push another and bump into them you see just for sport. And of course anybody that raised any objection they - the whole lot was ready to set on them, see. But this Tommy Potter that b
o
ught the little shop, he was all right because he'd got a brother who was a professional boxer who was the - who used to teach boxing to the Royal - the Honourable Artillery Corps, you know, on of the Guards Regiments I think it was or something similar n
o
t - not exactly a Guards but it was attached to the Artillery to modbile guns and - this fellow - he was used to rough fighting. He wasn't - I don't suppose he always stuck to the Queensbury rules but - he was used to a rough house with these soldiers and
 
he'd perhaps every evening or every - every day he'd been bashing about and taking bashings off of these - fighting with these rough customers so he wasn't afraid of anybody. And - or any number so to speak. So of course when Tommy got in and found out th
i
s trouble - was messing up his business he told his brother and his brother come down there you see and - got a day or two off. Came down there and when these fellows had all congregated outside and was larking about, singing, he went out and started swee
p
ing up the - forecourt. 'Cos it was a corner shop and got a wide pavement round the corner you know. So - he, you know, started sweeping up and he took care that the broom handle come up underneath one of them's jaw - hit him under the jaw you see with th
e
 broom handle. Well of course there was a swearing match for a minute or two and he dropped the broom and caught hold of the chap that was swearing and dragged him out in the middle of the road and knocked him down. Went back on the pavement and grabbed a
n
other one, took him out and knocked him down before the other one had time to get up and so after he'd - knocked one or two of them about he - he - the others started running away you see, they all started running away. So he shouted out after them, if - 
y
ou want any more come back tomorrow. So he stayed there for two or three days sweeping up every evening and they - they never put in any appearance and so - old Tom my he found - he found that was a little gold mine that shop, he did very well there. Him 
and his wife and couple of kids he'd got.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What sort of people belonged to the other groups you mentioned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh what you mean, the higher class people, well, couldn't tell you. The - the Colonel's people - there was a - what you might call a profes
sional class, well they were people that worked in offices. I knew some that were - stockbrokers clerks and - oh I don't know - well I don't - no, I don't remember knowing many - shop assistants. I had an Uncle that was salesman in the meat market and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about people in the lower classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh what the labourers you might say. The people that - well, you see, lots of them used to go up in the train but then their jobs were perhaps - pottering in the market you know - and - they were going up by 
the early trains. Well then there were people that stood outside the shops because most of the - the provision shops and that used to have somebody outside selling off a stall outside. People with jobs like that. People that worked in factories. 'Cos of c
o
urse lots and lots of girls they only got about - three or four shillings a week and a shilling of that went for their weeks railway fares. And then mum had got to provide them with sandwiches for dinner. And they very often didn't have any tea 'til they 
g
ot home you see. They'd leave off work about - five o'clock. They'd work from eight 'til five and get - well the - the forewomen they only - wouldn't get more than ten shillings a week for looking after a whole crowd of these girls working on a machine, y
o
u know, taking the papers off the machine as they come out - printing paper bags or something like that, you see. All those kind of jobs. Tremendous lot of that sort of work used to be done I don't know whether it is now, I - I doubt it because it's mostl
y done by machinery that's done away with all that hand work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. Not exactly. You were supposed to be respectful but I was forbidden on pain of a -
 cuff in the ear, for taking me cap off to a - a parson or taking me cap off to people of - you know - that - sort of expected - so that - well as I say there was a retired solicitor and a retired Captain of the Navy and goodness knows what lived along on
 
the same row of houses. We never - we always said good morning - good morning Sir or good morning Mr so and so or good morning Captain next door one side of as I say, the undesirable person, but the other side of us was a retired Colonel in the Army. Colo
nel Battersby. Well you see they were always very friendly, they said good afternoon, good morning, they didn't expect to - be treated with any special respect.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So you weren't expected to touch your cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, no. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was there anyone special you called Sir or Madam or Master?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. We might have said Sir to the guv'nor or - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 In the district where you lived who were considered the most importa
nt people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - I should imagine that the - it all depends what you'd call the most important people - the - there were the councilors or sometimes they weren't thought of with respect ; it all depended on what they were like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you come into contact with them at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
In their official capacity? Not that I know of. There was a councilor lived along our road but he was - that's what made me say about the respect they expected because half his time he was drunk. And - we thought to himsel
f - we thought to ourselves well it's a jolly good job if you get on the council because - I've seen - somebody come along there with a barrow and shoot - a couple of sacks of potatoes down his area so that all he'd got to do was open the door and take th
e
m in. All that sort of thing was reckoned to be marks of respect to the councilor. Someone who wanted to get his - his ear. Some blessings or other. But - but - otherwise - I don't know the - well actually that poor fellow - my brother one time was very k
e
en on helping with the - work amongst the down and outs and he used to go up there - there used to be breakfast given away and - White chapel I think it was - on a Sunday morning, particularly Sunday mornings for down and outs. And he went up there one or
 two times and who should be amongst the gang getting a free breakfast was this chappie that had been a councilor. He'd drunk it all away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know why they were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh well because they had some sort of position of authority you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you know who the shopkeepers would associate with
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, well they - they - had friends I suppose in general. They were a friendly as a rule, the shopkeepers. See there were no very large establishments there - there was the grocer an
d the - fishmonger. People like that. Oil - oil merchant. Uwd to sell paraffin oil and soap and - clothes pegs and all that sort of stuff. Chemist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Who would the teachers associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Who were the teachers? Well I should think their own sort 
of people. We used to know teachers - they used to - we used to meet with and mix with. Of course it might have been something to do with being fellow members of the chapel but - otherwise perhaps we shouldn't come into contact with them, they might move 
in a different circle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I should - I imagine that their friends would be - the people to - whom they owed their living in a way - their - people that contributed. Well you see the clergy are dependant for their living up
on the - the ecclesiastical commissioners. Any rate they had a very, very small sum of money allotted to the clergy officially. But in some districts there's what they call - the - some - a living which is money that's been left in a bequest - in a will, 
t
o benefit the clergy and of course there are people who contribute towards the upkeep of the clergy. Church members of standing, usually of course, they hold some position in the church - church wardens or something of that. At any rate the - they're the 
p
eople who - with whom the clergy associate. On the other hand of course the clergy are very - as a whole - are very - good at visiting the people, whether they're well to-do or whether - they're poor. And they visit all round. They're really friendly with
 everybody - they're after helping everybody.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you know any farmers round there - were there any in that area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - yes and no. One farmer that I told you when I was quite a small kid where you could go and get two penn'roth of potatoes and
 all that sort of thing. Well we had - our only contact with him was when we went to buy the stuff. But - we did become friendly with another farmer who was - very friendly to us. But whether - see farmers was all - always at work whatever time of day you
 
went if he wasn't - working on the land plugging or - seeding or something of that kind he was mucking out the pigs or something of that kind. He was always working. You see you'd got to - you went to visit him you'd got to go out with him where he was an
d talk to him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Who would the employers mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Couldn't tell you. I imagine what time they had they - mixed with other employers. If they were friendly inclined but I don't think people as a whole were - all that - socially inclined. There may 
have been social clubs and social - associations where they could meet together. The - young - the - our boss's son, he belonged to a cricket club, he belonged to a rifle club and - things like that. I think he also belonged to a social club but - the oth
ers of the family didn't have anything to do with it - they just stayed at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What sort of people would you say went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh, all kinds of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
How about the chapel - was there any difference between the people who went to church and the people who went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No I don't think so. The chapel people used to think that those - the - a lot of the ceremony at church was unnecessary and - side - it was a kind of a side track. And I think the church people used to think that -
 well they knew better than the chapel people that didn't - believe in all that they did. That's to say, didn't believe in the usefulness of all that - they did. Each had their own ideas as to why they should behave as they did. Of course a lot of the abu
s
es which made the chapels break away from the church in the first place - didn't - simply didn't exist in the - in those days - the days you're speaking - I'm speaking of, when I was a young person - a boy - a young man. See originally what caused the bre
a
kaway from the church was the abuses of the - people being in possession - in positions for what they could make out of it and - lots of them behave in a very disreputable - disreputable kind of way - that was to start with. A lot of insincerity - preachi
ng if they bothered to preach at all - preaching one thing and doing exactly the opposite.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well I couldn't say 
- there was a lot of difference between their - living standards of course but - I don't know they fell into different groups. You could say - you could say a tin smith belonged to a different group to a copper smith or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you des
cribe a family in the working class but in a different group from yourself
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, well of course I - I couldn't say. My mother made all our clothes but then so did mothers - many other mothers in similar positions. It was a case of the - what financial 
position they were in and whether they had to - well they had enough money to buy clothes all ready made.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Couldn't say but possible - possibly those who felt they were better educate
d than - the lower classes. There were swarms of girls working at - working as seamstresses - working for a few shillings a week making clothes. And - swarms and swarms of them because of course there wasn't the same mechanical for - facilities for doing 
it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, but that was due to their behaviour I imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was there a distinction of that kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 May be. Because in those- days - if you 
hadn't got enough money for your - for your people to keep you at school you could leave - you was eleven or twelve you could get work. And - or - plenty of people about even when I was at school that couldn't read or write although that was gradually bei
n
g done away with by the board schools and the board school officers, the school board officials that used to chase up the people that didn't go to school and - where it was a punishable offence to keep your children away from school. Gradually had it's ef
fect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I don't think so. She - she worked before she got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another - to better yourself or go down in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I couldn't say - really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You don't remember anybody that did at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - might have done once or twice. Owing to be a - associated with that aunt of my mother's that I say worked - lived among the - might - what you might call the upper class - she - she might have allu
ded to somebody as being a - titled lady. Oh you mean behaved like a lady or gentleman. Oh yes, had people that were outstanding in their good qualities - were recognized - they were recognised for it - they were credited with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember seeing a policeman round where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes. The police used to regular patrol - patrol regularly. But of course we lived - I - as I said, in the first place in the - on the main road and that may have made some difference but - oh yes, you would see policemen about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did you think of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well we - thought of them - well, as policemen. We recognized that they had got a certain amount of authority - that's to say whatever they said you'd got to do. And that you couldn't - do things that you oughtn't to do while they were looking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your mother ever threaten you with the police if you were naughty?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Not - not - not us no, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How do you think he treated the people in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well with respect. P
eople in general - he was friendly, he'd say good afternoon or good morning or whatnot and - if you got anything to ask him or complain about he'd try - he'd listen readily. And if there was any trouble he'd be on the spot. And - he'd be on the spot and y
ou - if you lost anything you could tell him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Your home wasn't rented was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. No it was - it belonged to me father. He bought it on a mortgage.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, they never had much money to spend - to - to spare but they - as far as I know they was never hard up, not - didn't have to go without anything to eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
What difference did it make to the family if your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well he was - he - I don't remember him ever being either. If he was ill he could generally manage to get to work - might have stayed at home for a couple of days with a - a very bad cold or something like that but otherwise he wouldn't - and it wouldn
't make any difference to his pay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
So you wouldn't ever have had any help from the Guardians or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Were you given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor or a governess before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 We were given
 a book to - ponder over and read and to ask questions about - I'm trying to think of the name of it. And it - it had got all kinds of pictures in of - and got the alphabet in it and pictures of animals and little - short little rhymes that you could lear
n
 off by heart. And that - that was given to us and we were encouraged to read it and as our parents read well and that and of course the younger - my brothers and sister, they saw me with it and - they joined in the reading of it and - borrowed it and rea
d it, or tried - you know - to learn the things off by heart so they could say 'em as if they were reading it. But that was - all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you read before you went to school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Only - only to recognize the pictures and that - kind of thing. 
'Cos I was only five years old when I went to school. And I could say these rhymes off by heart as if I was reading it but - and I could say the alphabet, I could say A.B.C.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You were five when you first started school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you go for a full day when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, it was a board school and you had to pay tuppence a week. For a time. Then that was made free - free education in the end. But I paid tuppence a week and - oh yes, I had to go in the mornings. I think we started
 at nine and we left off at twelve I think. And we went back again in the afternoon and came away about half past three, something like that - at first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was it a mixed school or just for the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 The children - the infants was a mixed school. W
e had girls as well as boys. But - as soon as ever the - they got to be - nine years old they were draughted out, the boys into a boys school and the girls into a girls school - they were - all three buildings were on the same - site. There was the infant
s school then there was a boys school and the girls school. And we draughted into those and kept separate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you get to school and how long did you take to get there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well it used to take five to ten minutes to get there and we used to walk
. Used to walk. There was no transport anyhow, not to the school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did anybody go with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well me mother went with me to start with but as soon as ever I could find me way myself I was allowed to go by myself. There was only one main road to c
ross and of course it was only horse traffic and - so - we could be trusted more or less by the time we - she'd seen me to school a few times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you go home for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh - pretty good. 
I can - I can remember feeling a bit frightened at first but of course we soon got used to it - plenty of other children there you see and - all marched into the schoolroom and - there was a Miss Barker was the - teacher there and she made everybody hold 
h
ands and march round the classroom because it - in the winter time you see it was perishing cold and they'd only got - this tremendous big high room and only just got ordinary fire with some coal burning in it. And that was only lit up by the caretaker fi
r
st thing in the morning you see so it was perishing cold to start with. And then she used to make us all hold hands and then she'd play the piano like with a marching tune and make the kids just go round singing a hymn you see and keep marching round, mar
ching round 'til they got their blood in circulation. And she'd let you wear your overcoat to start with. Before she started taking lessons. Oh it was good fun really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh they were very friendly. There was onl
y one teacher, that was in the - higher classes in the boys school, who was a bit - what we considered - spiteful or tough. He'd got a scheme for - if I'm not going too fast by talking about the boys school - anyway it was in the top class of the boys sch
o
ol - boys of thirteen and fourteen and - he got a scheme. When the - when he took over you went up into his class, he produced a cane and - very ostentatiously wrapped it up in a rag and put it away on top of the cupboard and said he'd hope he'd never hav
e
 to take it out. We'd all be well behaved. Then he - he kept his eye on the class and the way they behaved in - in lesson and in play and he'd see that there was one boy was reckoned to be the - top dog, you know, that nobody'd dare to push about, you kno
w
, someone that ruled all the others. Then he'd get - he'd find out too from the previous teachers about it and then that boy he'd give a slate and a piece of pencil and say well now look if I call another boys name out you write him down. If I call it out
 
again, put a mark against it. If I call it out the third time you tell me. And that's what he used to do you see, if you - if he saw me playing about or talking to the next boy he'd shout out my name. Written down on the slate. If I was called out again -
 then if I was caught the third time - out - out I'd go and get two handers. He'd call out you see, he'd say come out - out you go and you get two smart handers with the cane, have a sore hand for the rest of the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did the teachers emphasis certain 
things as important in life such as manners and tidiness, punctuality or ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I don't know about in life they - they taught you that at - to behave in school and you're supposed to be respectful, you're supposed to keep quiet, to ke
ep your mind on your work and to be tidy. If you were untidy or dirty you'd get called into question. Told off about it. If you - if your hands were dirty you'd be sent out to wash'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - usually you'd get reprimanded and perhaps get a smack - a spank but - as I say there was one teacher who was - got these methods of punishment. Oh hers were more chancy - if they were in a bad temper you'd get a strike with a cane. 'Cos ever
y teacher was issued with a cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were the girls punished the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 As far as I know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 For what sort of things would you get the cane?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well persistent disregard of the - rules of behaviour. For - for talking, sometimes yo
u might possibly get the cane for bad work if the teacher had got reason to think it - you was just careless, you were just not paying attention, that you'd scribbled it down without taking the trouble to form the letters or - because your mind was on som
ething else, but usually you were treated fairly respectfully - respectably - fairly kindly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes. They liked to know how you were getting on. They question you about it - what did you do - what did you do today and so on. And when you got - when they got the school report you see you - get - they'd check on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did they ever visit the school or go to meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, not that I know of. There was - there weren't any get to
gethers in those days. Do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh they came from all kinds of homes. All lumped together in age. There was one school that the boys could go to if their parents felt inclined to pay the - school fees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Not noticeably. Of course they were accused of having favourites but there were generally the children that were the brainiest in the - class. You know, there's reason for being - sort of - given a pat on the back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well boys were encouraged and - and that were - the children were encouraged to play games in the playground when they wer
e at play but - and I think - in the older classes - the classes when they're about to leave, it was just beginning to think about having a - a - football team or something of that kind. So that they could play against another class or another school. But
 
there wasn't much of that, not while I was at school. It got to be later on. While I was at school the upper - the top classes - the older classes - there was an antipathy to all other schools. An enmity against 'em and - as I say it - eventually it devel
oped up into a feud between one school and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were there any children left out of things at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, not that I know of. There - everybody was - brought into everything that was going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Then you went onto the boys school after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes. I went onto the boys school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What age would you go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Nine years old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 We have to go through the same questions again for this school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, well that - I've more or less answered them - the cane and - this - that wasn
't in the infants school - in the infants school there were just regular classes. The teachers were women you see and - they slapped you if you didn't behave and made you behave yourself - reasonable behaviour and tidiness and cleanliness. You't get into 
r
ow if you were dirty. And they used to send a note to your parents if your clothes were ragged, you see, and torn. You were given a note to take to your parents reminding them you - see that the children were supposed to be kept tidy. It was a bad example
 to other children if they weren't and would they see to it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
If children came without - proper boots and that the school people used to try and - get - some you know, get - were given by charitable people l
ike they do give 'em to bazaars and that, that they hold you see and they'd try and help people that were really down and out, they'd try and help you see 'cos there's no - no welfare then in those days. No welfare and so they - there was a good deal of t
h
at done amongst the teachers that if anybody was really badly off they used to get help, as far as it was possible in a small way like that. Like get a pair of boots or - some clothing, secondhand clothing perhaps handed out. What time did I leave school?
 When I was fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would you have stayed on longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh I think so. But you see my - my father had been a watchmaker - my grandfather had been a watchmaker and - you know, people that had worked at making watches - 
as a master man you see. The consequence was I had to be apprenticed and I had to serve a seven years apprentice. I had to learn to make the parts by hand you see, like they'd done. A great mistake because it was just dying out then. It was too late. The 
h
and made watch was destined to pack up. You see. And now would be a museum piece practically, you see. So of course I - I had to do - that's the first thing I had to do was to learn to use a lathe and - what they used to call turns, things that they used 
t
o use - a - a whalebone bow and a coarse hair to make the very fine - very small things. Just bringing it down and making a cut in it and to used all sorts of tools with - skill and accuracy and to be able to file a thing flat, you know, so that when you 
w
as filing a thing it didn't come a round surface - it'd come dead flat. That you could put a - a - straight edge along and there was no - no rounding off of it and that. All that sort of thing. And to work at - to a very fine limits. To a tenth of a thous
a
ndth of an inch. And - all that kind of thing, and to l - get a fine polish on things which you couldn't see a scratch on, not even when - with a magnifying glass. Oh all sorts of - of shall I say secrets of the trade there was - the kind of stuff to use 
a
nd the - the material that you used to put the polish on. See like for instance you couldn't get the finish on a - brass wheel - you couldn't get the dead mirror finish on it unless you got a block of tin and used stuff what they called red stuff which wa
s
 a very fine rouge. Very fine - been precipitated - you know, what they do is to put it in water in a jar of water and then it settles because it's heavier than water - the rough. It's really a kind of rust - been burned in a furnace. Rust burned in a fur
n
ace turns it red and then it's put in the water and it sinks to the bottom. Well there's - the very fine particles they're longer sinking down than the big lumps. Big lumps go right to the bottom straight away you see. 'course it's powdered up to start wi
t
h a hammer. Well then the finer the stuff is the longer it remains in solution and so that they skim off the top part and dry - and put it on blotting paper or rag and dry that off and then put that powder in again in some water. And finally in oil becaus
e
 oil - will keep things - and so until they get the very finest of it. Well if you get that very fine red stuff and - and polish your wheel - put it on a piece of cork - that's what we used to do, put it on a piece of cork, press it on, it makes a mark ro
u
nd the outside edge. You take a knife and cut the cork away so that it - the wheel stands up where nothing touches it what you put on it. Then you take your - your tin - virgin tin block, dab a little red stuff on it with your finger and then go round wit
h that. You get a mirror polish on it that - shows no scratches you see. Of course some of the watches, before the gilding came into - process - they were all polished you see, a very high polish, before there was any gilding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you attend any part time education after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes. I went to the British Horological Institute to learn the theory of watch making, you know, all about how the shape of the teeth is made - epicycloide and cycloideal curves on them to - so that the epicyde - e
picycloide tooth on a cycloidal pinion don't rub like that as it goes round but it just rolls - no friction, so that in the years of working the watch - they don't wear. Whereas those if they're just made - shaped up any old shape, they would - they slide
 
like that and after it's been going for about a year you'll see great ruts worn in the things where they've been working together you see. And then of course you've got to know about the angles - the two degrees of locim on a pair of pellets, fifteen degr
e
es impulse so it gives it a little push as the wheel goes by, it gives a push to push the balance you see. And then you've got to know all about the - curve of the hair springs so - with a watch that's got to keep fine - time you've got to have an overcoo
l
 so as to get regular - time, whether the balance is spinning far or not very far, with bending the spring see. If it's a flat spring well that - it's got a - a coil in it like that it goes much faster than if it is only going like this. So you have to - 
a
ll that sort of thing you have to learn. Then you have to learn how it is they got the time by taking a transit of the sun. And if you want better time still you've got to take a transit of the stars, what they call Siderial time. You've got to learn how 
t
o take the transit - to watch it, see like to know when the sun's at its peak so that you know when it - when it - goes - its highest point you see. And you get a - like at noon time we say - they used to reckon it see Greenwich Mean Time - the time that 
t
he sun goes over meridian. Because you see the sun goes like that - well if it goes - on the meridian the - the - the longitude of meridian of longitude from the centre of the earth to the pole - the north pole - you get a line. Well when the sun is exact
l
y the middle of the sun exactly over that meridian so to take - to get that time you take a - a - a transit there when it - as soon as the first - you're looking up a tele - you're looking through a telescope that's got a spider's web line little bit of s
p
ider's web it is taken, 'cos that's the finest line they can - could get. Course I'm talking about years ago, mind you, I can tell you more about time keeping now, they - well I can't tell you the very latest 'cos I haven't been in touch with it. But this
 
spider's web line, looking through this telescope at Greenwich which was fixed on a - so that it can't move you see, and it's looking on the meridian and then when the first rim of the sun as they see it come up comes up like a ball, touches the line, the
y
 - they - make a mark - a line - signal. Well then they watch that sun 'til it goes past the - just as the sun leaves the line they make another line then they take the time in between those two you see. They say that's the mean time - that's the - that's
 
the time when the sun was exactly on that meridian. And that was Greenwich Mean time. That was set all over the world. They had got a very accurate time keeping clock there which sends out those six pins. And they keep that regulated - so that - it's test
e
d every day and they - they tried it over a whole twelve months and it was - it was less than two hundredth parts of a second out - their signal. Send out six pips you see they - they - the last pip was the time and that pip was a two hundredths of a seco
n
d out - less than two hundredths of a second out the worst - amount of time it was out - sent out by that clock. But it's always checked by - always checked by the observatory you see. But now they've got a - a - the vibrations of a crystal that they reck
o
n is got - that don't have any variations at all. And that the vibrations of this crystal is kept vibrating by an electrical impulse and that - they don't reckon that varies at all and so the six pips they don't reckon that varies as much as the two hundr
e
dths part of a second or anything like it. Yes. So you had to learn all that - how to take the transit, why and how far away from the sun we are and how long it takes for use to get round the sun and - the stars - the nearest star - is - it takes - is it 
t
hree and a half minutes or something for the light to get here and that goes - or is it three and a half years - anyhow it's a - a long way away. Three and a half year - I think for it to get - the light to get - and that's travelling a hundred and eighty
 
thousand miles a second and it take three and a half years to get to that and that's Syrius a star which we don't see because it's - don't come in this - can't see it. Have to go south to see that. And you have to learn all that you see and that's what I 
d
id at British Horological - besides all kinds of things to do with the practical - measuring of angles and all that sort of thing as I say, the curves of teeth and - all this business of isocranaish as they call it - these - time keeping. It was quite pal
a
ver. I used to have to do - so many evenings a week, so many afternoons and then I used to - course had to do a terrific lot of homework. And then in addition to that I thought perhaps I might start up in business on me own and it'd be - it was usual for 
a
 watchmaker and optician to be in business, you see, he was - yes, a jeweller was usually an optician as well. And so I did a years course on optics but - I didn't - didn't carry that out because that faded out, that idea of - going into business on me ow
n
 at that time at any rate. So I didn't - I didn't pursue the optics. Beyond taking a certificate for - a certain amount of knowledge. But in the - the British Horological Business I got a - the British Horological medal which hadn't been given for three y
e
ars because you had to get over ninety per cent of all your marks and I got ninety-seven per cent out of a - out of an impossible hundred. I got ninety-seven per cent and so I got the British Horological medal. Because you have to get over ninety per cent
 
for - for drawing - British Horological drawing - that's for drawing all the various parts of watches and - all sorts of astronomical - things. And for - the - calculations part, you know, the - what do they call it - maths part of it. And - also for theo
r
y, you know, the theory part about the - the astronomy stunt. But I managed to get over ninety per cent in all them an aggregate of ninety-seven per cent and so I got the British Horological medal and congratulations. Went up to the - went up to the Guild
 
Hall and got a silver medal from the worshipful Company of Turners and - for practical work and I got the City and Guilds Honours Medal for it and the City and Guilds - both in - the - ordinary grade and the honours grade. So I didn't do too had out of th
e old British Horological.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh no. Oh no. Not much - I was going to say not much use to living really in a way but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well I expect so, yes.
 Didn't make me any better man or - I suppose it made me a better workman - it saved me from making a lot of fool mistakes that I might have done if I hadn't known better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. No. Didn't have any time you see, I went to - I started work like I had to catch the quarter to seven train to start with while I was apprenticed and I didn't get home 'til a quarter past nine at night. That was - as I say 
I was a boy of fourteen then so I didn't have much time or wish for anything more. And Saturdays we had to work 'til four o'clock. Meant quarter past five when we got home. Well then of course as hours went down - when I actually left off at - going to wo
r
k in that way I - worked from eight - half past eight, one place I worked at from nine in the morning 'til - five o'clock in the afternoon. Then of course when I went in the instrument making I did the hours that they did and any extra time I did was over
 time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Your first job was where you were apprenticed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. I held that for eighteen years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you get that job - was it through your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, through me father, he was a - mech - foreman of the workshop. Yes, my father was fo
reman of the workshop there - see it was all handmade work that was done there. Some of the workmen that worked there were only doing repairs but me father and myself - in - at the end of the time when I was there, not when I was apprenticed - when I was 
a
pprenticed it was - a great deal of it was handmade - making handmade watches. And of course at the last part of the time I was there - the workmen there were mostly on repairs. And we'd come down to doing just a very, very few handmade watches and some f
e
w special clocks like for ladies boudoirs and - something which the - the aristocrat could take up - take a lady up in to her bedroom and say - oh what a lovely little clock. 'Cos it was something that they couldn't buy anywhere - couldn't see anywhere el
s
e and you see it was like nothing else that they'd ever seen and - how lovely - I wish I could get - where did you get that, you see. So - that sort of thing you see that's what - there was just a little bit of that going on but as soon as ever the - livi
n
g went down and the aristocracy faded out our trade faded out with it you see, and we come down onto repairs. And then of course the Jew boys that had got all the - chalk and brush people working, they got all the repairs because they were prepared to - g
e
t a watch and dip it in a drop of benzine and - blow it out with a pair of bellows and had it back as having been cleaned and repaired you see, at a shilling a time you see, something like that. And the man who really took the watch to pieces - repaired a
ll the worn bearings and turned it out as equal to new he - well he was right out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When you first went there as an apprentice what exactly did you have to do?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well the first thing I had to do was to make screws. The little screws for watche
s. I was given the job of making screws. And - so I - issued with a piece of steel and I turned the piece down for the - and - and put the thread on it and then - cut the piece off and shaped up the head and then when I got a number of them I hardened the
m
, tempered them, then polished the head and then heated it to turn it to the proper blue colour or what our firm called the plum colour which was the colour they wanted on their watches. And when I'd finished and made a little tin box full of these screws
 
I took them down to show the guv'nor that - the boss for - for his approval. Oh, he said, oh yes, quite good. And shot 'em all out in the wastepaper basket and gave me the box back and said, now make another box full. Very encouraging. Very encouraging. T
h
en of course I - gradually after I - done a lot of screws I was put on making other parts - the bearings and - you know, like the thing the balance spins on and - well, turning down the cog wheels and actually finally I was entrusted with work in the mach
i
ne - worked by hand for cutting the teeth on the wheels and so on you see. So that - of course long before I'd served my seven years I was quite a useful - person, but I had to serve my seven years apprenticeship. And - at that time I - you know, got from
 filling up lumps of brass and all that sort of thing and making wheels and doing all sorts of things like that to taking them round to the gilders and having them gilt. All that kind of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I worked from - when I was
 apprenticed I worked from eight 'til eight. And then - I was never home before quarter past nine. I had to start out - at - be - catch a train round about seven o'clock and I was never home before quarter past nine. And five o'clock on Saturdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So you worked eight 'til four on Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Eight 'til four on Saturdays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And you didn't work Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Didn't work on Sundays ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You didn't have a half day during the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have any holidays with pay while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, never had any holidays with pay. We were allowed Bank Holidays - not at first. At first we didn't have any holidays. If you had a holiday you - you asked for time off. You might have a day off or something like that without complaint bu
t you had to - leave - you didn't get any pay for that day. But if you - had sauce enough to ask for a week off or - that, he'd tell you to get yourself another job because they could - you know, somebody else who didn't mind working. And so - I did know 
somebody that left over that, a man named Barber. He wanted a weeks holiday because - he was a widower when he came to work for us and - he met a lady in a pub and he - she was a widower and eventually they decided to get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  and he wanted to go a honey
moon, or have a week off anyhow to enjoy themselves. And so he demanded a weeks holidays and they said well - you know - you no need to comeback. Got somebody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you remember what you were paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, I was paid, when I first started I was
 paid two shillings a week. Yes. But - then I got - worked to gradually ten shillings and when I finished - in my last year apprenticeship I got thirty shillings a week. Well thirty shillings a week you could get a chalk and brush man for that. 'Cos they 
w
ouldn't get very high wages then. A porter on the railway got eighteen shillings a week. But - so it was better than that. But I - I wouldn't stand for that. I left and got a job for - two - guineas a week at a place named Halfords in - in Fenchurch Stree
t. And then after I'd been there - about three months they gave me fifty bob a week to go back. So I - that's what my wages were while I worked at the watch work there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
When you first started and got two shillings a week did you feel that was a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh well I didn't - I didn't have any say in the matter. It wasn't up to me to think anything you see that was what I was supposed to do. You see, I got a job, they had to pay me something, well - 'course my fares cost me - tuppence a day t
hreepence a day on that because I was on a threepenny train you see 'cos I didn't go up quite so early as me father had to. He didn't either, we got the - by that time we got the later trains you see. I went up on a threepenny train. And then eventually a
fter the terrific outcry about the trains we got on the - the ten past seven.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you give any of that two shillings to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well I handed it all to her really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And she handed it all back to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, well she had to pay out m
y railway fares you see and that. And buy that - money for the stuff for me sandwiches that I took with me for me dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you get along with the people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 All right. 'Course I was errand boy first, that's how I - as I say, 
making screws and was sent - they wanted a - some part that you could buy, was sent across to the shop to buy it you see, or if we wanted some metal - down to St John's Square to - get it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh - quite reasonably you know, friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you feel about him - did you like him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh - we didn't like the young guv'nor much 'cos we thought he was trying to get more out of us than - than the old guv'nor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How did you feel about the work - did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes, I liked the work. Oh yes, you see, there was a - about half a dozen people sitting in a row, see - our - the rank file sat in a - on a bench in a row in front of a long window - like it might be the side of a greenhouse so there was plenty o
f light on our benches you see. Well our bench where me father and I worked was - oh - eighteen inches - oh I liked work - it was interesting - tire - tiresome as I think I told you, that I had to start making screws and when I'd finished making a box ful
l
 of screws - there must have been - oh, hundreds there really, and I'd used up the length of steel making all these screws and hardening them and - tempering them and then polishing them up and then colouring them by warm - heating them up - a few at a ti
m
e on a little - brass box on the end of a wire, holding it over a spirit lamp and colouring them up and then - took them down to the boss and he - looked at 'em said, oh yes, oh they're all right. And then threw them in the paper - waste - paper basket an
d
 said, make another lot. I got a bit peeved over that. And of course the work of learning to make things was a bit tedious - to - as - for a time. But it was very interesting work. And once you got used to doing some of it because you could see something 
f
or the work you put in. We were always trying to make something that was - good and if you could see some of the old fashioned watches taken to pieces - the old handmade watches taken to pieces you'd find that the finish on the parts that were made was ab
s
olutely perfect and not to be - modern machine made article is not to be compared with it for the - trouble that was taken to - make 'em perfect. The - the shoulders where the pivots finished off were polished to a brilliant - polish, mirror polish and th
e
 edges were chamfered off - bevelled off and a great deal of trouble was taken to - make possible - skilled work. Say for instance between where the - pivot was that turned in the framework - what sit the wheels turned on between where - that came up into
 
the brass plates and where the cogs started that was sloped backwards so as to leave another square surface that could be polished like a mirror you see and the slope was polished. The ting had to be absolutely perfectly polished. Tremendous lot of hand w
o
rk was done absolutely unessential as far as the going of the watch was concerned but it was - exhibition of skill on the part of the man who did the work. It's - it stemmed from the fact that the people who actually were watchmakers to start with who mad
e
 a watch making their life work - the people that invented different kinds of watches, different types of works - escapements as they called them and - gradually perfected the watch they - they did their best to turn out a masterpiece, you see, it had to 
b
e a master piece of workmanship as well as ingenuity. But if you - if you get very old watches you see that demonstrated in each one you pick up. The old hand made clocks are the same you see, they took a lot of trouble, through it was a - primitive sort 
o
f mechanism and perhaps - hand forged a lot of the parts it - a lot of trouble was taken to put a good finish on it - to make it what they called a masterpiece. And you could see it demonstrated if you could see a museum clock, you see all - all kinds of 
refinements on it where they'd taken the trouble to put a pattern on it and all sorts of things. Not necessary to make the clock go or keep time or anything but - simply a demonstration of skill.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you stay in that job up until 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh no. I 
worked at watchmaking - making watches by hand - up 'til about the time of the Boer War, whatever time that was, 190-something - 1902 was it. No. Later then that. I couldn't tell you without looking at an encyclopedia or something to see what time the Boe
r
 War was. But when the Boer War started there was a bit of a slump in the jeweler trade because a lot of people went away to the war and a lot of people had got money invested which - would jeopardized during the war - a lot of money - people lost money -
 
in the Boer War and the results afterwards. The charge it was on the nation - the money it cost this country to be in the war. The consequence was that - the jewellery trade suffered quite a set back. And our trade fell off tremendously. And - then - was 
the start when the Swiss made wrist - wrist watches began to get on the market over here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You stayed there and did seven years apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, I did seven years apprentice and then I became what they called a journeyman. And as I say I left 
where I was apprenticed because the wouldn't pay me full wages and took a job in - in the city and worked there for a time and then - my - the - I - they offered me thirty shillings a week where I was apprenticed. Well I took a job for - forty-five shilli
n
gs a week and the - where I had been they offered me fifty shillings a week to go back. Well I was pleased to do that because I was a bit fed up with the other job because - I was - had to - dress - I was expected to dress as a gentleman. And appear on an
 
equal with the shop assistant people. I - the manager there - sort of resented anybody coming there with any pretensions and the consequence was he tried to come it over me and actually he actually did play a trick on me over the work in order to get me r
i
p - reprimanded by the bosses and - for carelessness. I was absolutely innocent of you see. And just about that time the - the other people offered me five bob more a week than I was getting to go back and so I left and went back again to where I was appr
e
nticed. And I worked on there for eighteen years. Altogether. I worked there for eighteen years altogether when I left. And I left to go and work, because I was called up in the first world war but because - because my sight was very short sighted - I'm v
e
ry short sighted - I could see very well and work on very accurate work - was used to working on very accurate work - I was sent to do work of national importance and they put me to work in the - in a small arms factory. And I - I was lucky there because 
t
hey put me on the job in a section - the work has divided up in sections. There was a batch of men working on - drilling holes through a piece of steel to make the barrels out of you see, there was batches of men working on the drilling. And then there we
r
e the batches of men working on the cutting the rifling, you know, those grooves up inside the barrel. And then there was people who - cut the - breach end back and made a screw thread on it so that when it was screwed up tight in a stock where the sights
 
were was in the right place and all that sort of thing. All those were done in sections you see. And I was put on a section - and - to do with making the screw and - so that it screwed up in the right place where it was bang tight you know - it - securely
 
screwed up ting in place - the flat part on the barrel came in just the right place you see. Well the old lockies they were - they were very careful to see that the newcomers didn't work so quick as the old ones, you see. And to cut - the - the barrels al
r
eady drilled and rifled and cut to length and - the nose end was rounded up so that the - the tip of the barrel was all finished. And you had to put that in the machine and it had to fit on a little socket - a spout and when you started the machine runnin
g
 oil would pump through the barrel from a - tank underneath the machine so that when you started doing the - cutting on it the tools were lubricated. And I had to - put a - reamer into this barrel that started the cartridge chamber and out the thing back 
t
o the right length for it to screw and put - and so the screws then could be put on - I didn't have to put screw thread on but I had to cut it back to the right length and roughly bore out the cartridge chamber. So - the old lockies, they took part of the
 
machine away. So that the man who was - the - man who was a lot - old lockie - man who was working up the other end of the line of machines, all he got to do was to put his barrel in and push it in and when the slide rest up against it - where they've got
 
a copper - lump of copper there that used to hit it and knock it up tight. The taper part used to fit in tight so you could - then you could do the turning operations on it you see. They took that guide that used to guide that onto the stuff - took that a
w
ay. So that I'd got to push it in with one hand and then put the other hand in and lift it about 'til I felt it go on to the thing and then bump it in you see. Well that took, me - although I'd got pretty quick at doing that I could never match the who co
u
ld just push it straight in. Well I - I found out you see that I was doing much less in number than what he was per day. And I thought, there must be something in it. And I took the trouble to go and have a look at his machine - I took the trouble to look
 
- walk past him several times during the day and - see how he was - what he was doing 'cos the machine seemed to be exactly the same in every - as far as I could see. And I noticed him just putting the thing in and bumping it up you see, so I thought, wel
l
 there must be some sort of guide there doing it 'cos I was used to using a lathe and all that sort of thing in my work, only of course much smaller. So in the dinner hour I took the trouble to go and have a look you see, a more close look at his machine 
a
nd I saw what was missing. So when I went home I made myself one on my lathe - I made a boxwood arrangement, I hadn't got any steel or no means of getting a chunk of steel I could make it out of, so I made it out of boxwood. And I fitted it in my machine 
a
nd then I was up to him in the number of barrels I turned out. Well of course directly I did that they wanted to know why. They came round to look you see, fortunately for me - the - chappie who was in charge of all the - the - that section - he had a loo
k
 too you see. So he thought to himself, oh that chap is - you know, he - he - he's made a good job of that and - you know, he'd probably be good at something other things you know that require a bit more - what shall I say - skill, more - a bit more - use
d
 to being working with tools you see. So he transferred me onto a bench and - it - put me on the job of making the tools that - or keeping the tools up to snuff - to start with - on the tools that were making the cartridge chamber. Well that had to be pre
t
ty accurate, the cartridge chamber because there's - nearly twenty tons pressure in the breach when that's fired, like the first eight inches of barrel when the explosion occurs - there's - over nineteen tons pressure in the breach you see, momentarily to
 
the bullet goes out. There's all that pressure pushing it out you see. And so if the brass cartridge case isn't backed up by the steel barrel all the way round it the cartridge chamber it rivets itself in you see and then the extractor - if it's a machine
 
gun that automatically throws out the old cartridge case and puts another one in to fire - or in a case of a - a rifle, you operate the bolt and - and push it out you see. So - and if it's got any scratches round it it'll fix in you see and you can't get 
i
t out. And if it happened to be a bit too large if it was - if it's more than three thousandths of an inch large the cart - cartridge case will split an -- under the pressure and so on. So it has to be pretty accurate. So they put me on that job - try me 
o
ut on that. I succeeded. The consequence was that - eventually I was put in part charge of a section, you know, to be there when the other chappie was away or - all that sort of thing and - responsible for a whole line of machines turning out the barrels 
w
ith the cartridge chambers cut in them you see. And so I got some sort of a standing there that - made things much easier for me - I was able to make myself a drop of tea and - all that sort of thing and - wasn't quite the same thing as being - driven and
 kicked about on all, you know, all sorts of ways like they - did. So I was lucky in that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you there all through the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I was through there right through the war. And then of course directly the war was over - there was a bit of trouble t
o start with because everywhere - the people were coming back and being demobbed out of the Army and there was no work for 'em and there was gatherings all over the place gathering together and demanding work and demanding. See there was no such - no - ou
t
 of work pay then and the consequent was there was a lot of troubles and they put - big posts in all - all the way up the road leading to the small factory, put posts in so you couldn't march all together in an army. You could only go wone at a time and t
h
read your way through the posts, you - could - no make - making a dsh - they took all the locks out the machine guns and sent them away somewhere else so the machine guns had go no - couldn't - couldn't come up there and assault the factory and grab the m
a
chine guns and used them on the - Government. You see, there was all sorts of precautions taken like that. Then of course everybody that wasn't - an old lockie got the sack. Well of course, I thought I should be able to go back to my old job in Clerkenwel
l
 that I'd had. But - they weren't at all ready to have no back there and - in fact they offered me about an errand boys wage to go back. They would have tried - they would have found me some work to do but - altogether it was very poor and so I - started 
u
p on my own. Got - and started repairing watches because gradually - the people that had got money and got good watches, they found that all the watchmakers had been drafted into the Army you see they - all the watchmakers that could do anything, they'd a
l
l got shoved in the Army and lots of them like me had found a job where they was - earning - earning - better pay than what they got at watch making. Because wages had gone up a bit so - me father had - me father, he - still kept at work for a time but ev
e
ntually he left and joined me and we worked together for quite a time and did quite well repairing watches - watches that required new parts which the average - what we used to call - a chalk and brush man, that could clean a watch but couldn't replace an
y
 of the parts especially if it was a good watch as I say that had got workmanship in it, see, that - they couldn't replace a thing and the consequence is that people that could get a fair amount of work. So we did fair - quite well for quite a while. Got 
a
 lot - you see, then again, the war had got to be paid for and the people that had got money invested in foreign securities like in the Argentine and in the East India Company and - in the Hudson Bay Company and all the American projects you see where the
 money was invested and they was getting enough interest to keep them so they'd still got their capital and they was getting enough interest to keep them so they'd still got their}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 capital and they was - the money was coming in like money sent from the bank 
which they could live on and they'd got houses were they'd got twenty servants some of them. Parlour maids and house maids and kitchen maids and butlers, see, and footmen to stand up behind the carriage as they drove out and all that sort of thing you see
,
 they - they began to find that their money was vanishing and did vanish and a lot of the big houses were shut up - and eventually a lot of the big houses have become trust property. You see, General Peron took over the Argentine and all the people that h
a
d got money invested in the - cattle farms lost a lot - never got ha'penny lot of them. So the consequence was their income stopped and all the people that was buying - spending any sort of money if they could get something that nobody else had got that t
hey could boast about and swank about you were - didn't want any more and so we found things very difficult.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did you do after that - did you carry on working for yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well - yes. Somebody that we knew - did us a - disservice by pretend
ing that he could put us in the way of earning a living or getting a living. You see, he was a manager of a chemist's - in Boots and - he told us or told - yes, told us you see that when - he happened to know we was looking about for some - business where
 
we could start up and serve the public because up to then you see we'd been working for - top class jewelers in the - like people that had got - shops in Piccidilly and - all that all the big - topnot shops you see, but that could afford to pay us good pr
i
ces for our work because they could get ratting good prices off the people that they were dealing with, see, or that were dealing with them. Well, then you see when that stopped and - you couldn't get any of that sort of work all you could get was chalk a
n
d brush work and there was plenty of Jews to do that well - and go and get them one day and take them back the next - all they'd done was just dip them in a - a bottle of benzine and - blow 'em dry with a pair of bellows and - just let 'em go at that. And
 
so we couldn't stand that and we thought we'd start severing the public because then we could get the money that - without any rake off - be - you know, for - somebody paying us to do work while they took the profit. So we was looking around for it and th
i
s chemist man found out what we was doing and he said - he - he'd moved - he'd moved away from Enfield where he had been and - he said well shy don't you start up in the boarding house business? He said, people are making fortunes in Clacton-on- Sea. Peop
le paying no end of money, he said, and I've got a brother down there that's - or down here - it was in Clacton, you know, that's doing quite well at boarding. And so, why don't you have a go at that and you could - you could still keep on you\rquote 
re your - wor
k for the - what little work you've got, see what work - what connection you've got, he said, you might - you might work up another connection in Colchester because that's a big place where they've got big jewelers and - you could do that in the - in the 
m
ean - and your wife could look after the boarding house and get on all right. But of course he - he got a - a motive in getting us down there it was a good motive so far as he was concerned but it was ruin - ruinous to us because we took on to - a big hou
s
e down there, you see, much too large for what we wanted to live in to do - boarding and - you had - we had to work, and particularly my wife had to work - work herself to death. And Elsie could tell you something about that - what that was like and of co
u
rse, it was two farthings for a ha'penny, couldn't make money for it - out of it. So we had a - very rough time down there, we stuck if for quite a long time - I don't know how long it was altogether. But - was about fourteen or sixteen years I should thi
n
g. We were still doing watch repairing and - watch and clock repairing and struggling about and poor - my poor wife was - you know, working herself do death, you know. Getting up at three o'clock in the morning sometimes and - you know, preparing for the 
cooking and - stuck there working and directly the peoples out of the way, doing out the bedrooms, see. Terrible Elsie could tell you something about that 'cos she fell into a lot of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What did you do after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well - I packed it up. I got a
 - job in London and - I packed it up and - or least I worked in London for a time you see, where I was getting wages and - wife - gradually worked up there and eventually went there to live. And - I was able to go home and - I - had to go up to London ev
e
ry day you see to work and then - a friend of ours at - well it was somebody that came to preach at our hall, he was a - a - well, one of a team that was running a factory - a new factory had started up in - Enfield. It was an American factory - the Sanga
m
o Western or - Sangamo, it was called the British Sangamo when it started. It was the Sangamo - Electrical Company or something like that out in America. Because it was on the banks of the Sangaman River. And - they used to sell electricity meters over he
r
e. And of course there was no electric meters weren't used by the - government then and by - it wasn't nationalized - there were certain companies you see, there was English Electrics and there was the Tottenham and District Electricity Board and all that
 
sort of thing and - so there was a trade in these meters. Well Ediswans were making meters as well. And - so - the there was some changes in the government and then finally they decided to put a tax - up to then the tax - everything could come in this cou
n
try tax free, see if Americans could make watches cheaper than what we could make 'em here well then they could be sold cheaper because they could come in - they'd get a shipload of 'em and unload 'em on the market you see and - that was that, they didn't
 
have to pay. But then suddenly the government started putting a charge on everything that came in - like the Americans used to charge if we sent things out there. Like the Swiss people'd charge if we went things - watches to them. They wouldn't have 'em w
i
thout we paid a big duty on them, so they started putting a duty on the meters. And - so much so that when the - there was a slump and the - government devalued the pound down to twelve and sixpence was it - what the people had saved - all the money that 
I
'd saved or the wife and I had saved - every pound went down to be worth twelve and six. Well you see if you drew a pound out what you'd put in at a pound if you drew it out it was only worth twelve and six for what it'd buy you see. 'Cos it went down dir
e
ctly. Well it did the same in America. The consequence was that American meters that cost them a pound to make could only be sold for twelve and six when they got here so they thought, oh well, what we'd better do is to send the bits over and - put 'em to
g
ether in - see the bits won't have to pay duty - the meters would. But if we send over the little bits they won't have to pay a duty on them and we'll get someone to put 'em together so they did. They started up - they got a - rented a - a - section of Ed
i
swans factory and - employed men to come and work at it and so they put the - made their meters over here and put on the market over here, you see, so they got - their meters put together at the twelve and six value of the pound wages against what they we
r
e paying over there you see, so they were able to come back on the market and - be at the English Electrics and other meters for price so - that's how it started. Well then gradually - business increased and competition got hotter so they decided that the
y
 would start up and make the things here. And they did. So they started up this British Sangamo they called it and they were very successful. And this person got me a job there. He happened to be this - he used to come to preach at our hall occasionally a
n
d - I don't know how it cropped up but anyhow I - something occurred - brought it up and he - my - my wife was - Elsie's very friendly with his wife over her Bible class and that. They sort of had interchange of help and that and so eventually he got me a
 
job at this place. Making the experimental things up, 'cs you see there - in all those things there's a - great competition. I you can bring out something new that's a bit cheaper to produce or to do something more than somebody' else's will that's - that
'
s it. And so it - there's always improvements going on. See - was slot meters you see, well you could put a penny in the slot and then somebody brought out - a shilling in the slot I mean, and then somebody brought out a meter - meter that you could put a
 
penny in the slot as well as a shilling, and somebody else brought out a meter that you could - that you could - pay, if you had a new cooker you could pay for it by - on instalments by the money you - put in the meter because every shilling you put in th
e
 meter for - to pay for electricity they took threepence off to pay for - towards paying the instalments on your cooker, see. So that all those sort of things were brought in. All - so I worked on that sort of work for a long time. Then - there was a firm
 
over there that had been doing the same sort of thing as the meter people - the Sangamo meter people, was making instruments like volt meters and - measuring, electrical measuring instruments, you know for measuring how much juice is going through the - m
a
ins and measuring all sort of things, you know, like you see - when - like your car breaks down somebody comes and put things on the - you know - got a little dial, you can see what's happening. Well those sort of things and - aircraft instruments. And th
e
y were sending the parts over and getting them assembled over here and suddenly they - I don't know how it was - Sangamo's and these Westerns people got together and Sangamo's took them over. Allowed some of their personnel to come and take jobs in Sangam
o
 and agreed to employ all their work people, which they did for a time then they soon - soon they - they gradually shot them off you see. Well then they - they - we started making these meters there. So of course our department where I was working was ext
r
a busy because we got loads of drawings to make things up to put in the works - to put in the works to - be made by the - mass production methods. Because Westerns you see had been making these machines very largely by hand labour but rows and rows of peo
p
le getting the parts they got sent over from America, putting 'em together and making 'em work but - in Sangamo's you see, they'd got all girls working in a row - in rows. One could do her operation six times as quick as the one working next to her and so
 
of course they put two girls here and four girls there and four passing them on one to another. In lots of cases going on a belt so they just picked 'em up as they came opposite, did what they got to do and they went on to the next person. And so that the
y
 could - they could actually make a meter when what - English Electric was getting thirty shillings for, Sangamo's could make for seven and six. By mass production. And that's what they were doing. So of course our shop was very busy. And so I had a good 
job there. I was there for twenty years. And even now they send me a box of biscuits at - Christmas time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were you there until you retired then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
And invite me to a dinner, yes, invite me to a dinner Christmas time - the firm's dinner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would you have preferred another type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. Oh no, that suited me very well 'cos it was - you see, they wanted somebody that could make by hand the same things as would be turned out by the automatic machines with the same degree of accuracy.
 So that you had to - sometimes some parts of the things you were held to a tolerance of ten thousandths part of an inch - of a thousandths part of an inch. A thousandths part of an inch. So you it was very careful work and you had to be able to do it you
 see - by hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
You saved an apprenticeship of your first job - did you on any of your other jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you belong to any trade union of professional organization?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well yes, I belonged to a trade union for a short time. But -
 you didn't have to belong to a trade union in the Sangamo at that time - I think - you have to now because the trades unions have - threatened to go on strike and the Sangamo people they paid higher wages than what the - standard wages were for those - y
o
u know, for engineers and that sort of thing. I believed most part of the time the men that worked in the tool room, that's making the tools for the mass production operations, they - the dies for staping out the wheels and all that sort of thing, the peo
ple that made those, they - they all had to be members of a trade union I believe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When you did belong to the union did you take part in any of the activities?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests or different ones?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well - yes and no. They - they started a scheme that worked very well in - Sangamo's and - by paying - a bonus - to people that did over the standard rate. But of course it was - the majority of the work except for the skilled work that was don
e in making the tools and that sort of thing, preparing the operations, it was all done on machines. And a girl could come there and in a - well about three weeks time she could - keep up with the regular rate of production and the production was settled 
b
y what they - they had people come round, watch the girls at work and see that they kept - kept on working and then that was a - there was a certain - percentage allowed for things that might go wrong but they were held down to a certain number of - opera
t
ions per hour or per day you see and they were looked - looked as being responsible to turn that much out. Well then in addition to that the Sangamo would allow 'em a percentage that amounted to a shilling or two - a few shillings a week if there output -
 
say three girls was working on one machine, like they did very often, they - the three girls who worked together on that machine, if they turned out this bonus amount of work they got a bonus at the end of the week to share between them you see, extra out
put. And - there was - in that - to that extent they felt they were in common. But of course the - the Sangomo was out to make profit and if they could have got it done at half the price they would have done. To that extent they were - in opposition.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about in your first job where you were apprenticed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh that - there was no unions - no union - no trade union in that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you feel that the employers and workers had the same interests there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well - as I say, yes and no. The rank and f
ile they may not have done - they felt of course they got the - there was people - but me - my father and I we were working on - different class of work and as I say there was a great ambition to turn out work that couldn't be matched. And to that extent 
w
e - they - we were - in agreement you see, we were trying to do the best we could and our boss was - he - his aim as well to be able to - put a watch into the shop that was going to sell it, a watch that couldn't be - equaled by anybody else. And that's h
ow - you see, that's how it was we could sell watches that were for a long time - we were able to sell watches that weren't saleable in the ordinary market. You'd got to find somebody that'd got lots of money and didn't mind spending it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 In your first 
job would you say there were divisions of interest amongst the workers themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh well, I don't know about that. Only to the extent that - my father and I as I told you, we worked on a - we were about three foot above them so that we could look d
own and see what they were doing. And see that they weren't doing work for themselves because it was easy enough for them to bring in a watch for a private customer you see, if they'd have been left to themselves they would have done and - well they did d
o a bit I expect, as it was. You see, but - so to that extent there was the - they were all - for - looking after themselves you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Some people say that in those days there was a great division between crafts on and other workers - did you feel that or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I don't know. You - you sort of felt you was a cut above the - porter on the railway line - all he did was to slam the doors shut on the carriages, that sort of thing and got eighteen bob a week. Well then you see if you was getting
 fifty bob a week doing watch making you was a cut above him in that sense. But - he was still a man wasn't he - to that extent. I don't think there was any particular - except that you felt that you could do something that he couldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would - you sa
y that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, except that I - I - had to do - had to work all those hours and - do as I was told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. I left home 'til I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 . I worked at home 'til I got - or lived at home I should say - I lived at home 'til I got }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did starting full time work change your relationship you\rquote 
re your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, not at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Or your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you spend your Sunday any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You still went to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, still went to the - service in the morning, to Sunday school in the afternoon and to the service in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you take an interest in politics at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way or did you do different things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I didn't have any spare time. Well - I might have done Saturday afternoon - Saturday evening. I - see at first I ha
d to work 'til for o'clock Saturday. Well there wasn't much time left by the time I got home, see it took an hour and a quarter to get home. But - later on we left off at four - at one o'clock. That left an afternoon clear. But - I used to spend my aftern
oon, until I started courting, much about the same as I did - before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you go out in the evening at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well I wasn't home 'til nine o'clock - quarter past nine in the evening.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about Saturday evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh Saturday - no, not - mi
ght have done once or twice but - not - nothing special. Might have gone to the circus if there was a circus there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Who would you have gone with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Me brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you make any new friends, boys or girls, at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. No because - 
in fact I lost the friends I'd got in a way because they went to work somewhere else and I went to work in London the consequence was we didn't see one another. Except at weekends and on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 If you did go out did your parents expect to know where you - were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I suppose they did - I don't know as any - they didn't - they did know where you went. I suppose they asked, where you going? Or what you going to do? We should certainly tell them, we wouldn't need asking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have to be home by a certain time if you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I expect so. You see, when we were younger we did have to be but when we got older, well, we didn't - we weren't tied down quite the same, we were - as long as we were home time to go to bed a reasonable hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What age were you when you got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Twenty-four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How long had you known your wife then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I'd know her - I'd known her I was going to say all me life really, I'd know her I suppose - oh - since I was about ten or eleven because 
I - you see, I knew her brother. He was a sort of a school friend of mine for quite a long time - indeed 'til he - 'til we left school. He was a friend of mine, he went to work at - some place locally - a local factory and I went to work in London so we d
i
dn't see one another. But I met her - I've got a photograph of her actually, Elsie's got one in her room, of when I first knew her. She's quite a little nipper. But of course I didn't - have any ideas of - she was my - my friends kid sister you see. 'Cos 
s
he was much younger than what he was. She was about six years younger than what he was and anyhow she was my - my pal's kid sister. And a bit of a nuisance to him actually because - he used to - she was a pal to him at times because when he used to go bat
h
ing in the lee she - she used to go sometimes to mind his clothes see that nobody bumped off with 'em - it was against her parent's commands but she did do so. And another thing he used to go - he used to make pocket money by selling birds - catching chaf
f
inches and greenfinches and birds - mostly finches - over - on the marshes with a brick trap you know, making 'em out of bricks. And she had - well, was too kind hearted to let that go on and so she used to after he'd been and set his traps she used to ni
p
 round when he'd come back, she'd nip out and kick all the traps over. So she was in his bad books. At any rate she started work and I happened to see her and I thought what a lovely girl she was - she'd got very fair hair, it hung down on her, not on her
 
shoulders because they used to be tied in a - in a bunch like, used to - it was right down as low as her waist her hair. She got lovely red cheeks and - I took to watching her for a time. Then - you see we both went to the same - the same chapel - the sam
e
 mission hall and then I - she used to help to teach the infants, they were upstairs and the stairs were like these little old places are - got a very - like our stairs are here, got a very dangerous sort of twist at the turn of the stairs. And the conseq
u
ence was that if the kids came down near the - side they were likely to toppe, head first over because they'd only got - got nothing to put their feet on. So some of us bigger boys out of the Bible class used to line up there, two of us, and catch these k
i
ds when they got to - near to the bottom you see, catch them under the arms and put 'em down you see so they didn't have to come down the last few stairs. So I used to - when I - as I say I took to watching her and finally to waiting to see her come down 
- when the last of the kids had come down I didn't go home, I still waited you see. So I got - struck up more close acquaintance with her. As I say, I knew her for many years. She knew me that far you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you save up money before getting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did your parents help you in setting up a home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well yes and no. They gave us some things you know and - we were - set up all right when we started. I think they gave us a table. Oh yes, they gave us a table and - oh - various
 things they gave us. An old armchair. Oh various things. Can't think of them all. We, as I say, we'd already bought a house. We let if for a twelve month and then took it over.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How long were you engaged.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 It was a new house. Two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
'Course we'd been keeping company for - well as I say, for years I suppose, I don't know how long - about six years I should think - four - four at any rate, actually going steady as you could say but we - I didn't have ov
er an engagement ring and didn't absolutely - say we were going to get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
 'til about a couple of years before we got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 . And then what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Could you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well it was very simple sort of affair. The - there was - we ordere
d - three carriages to take the guest and - we - went in one and the guests from our house went in one and the guests from my wife's house went in one. Went up to the place and this - the service - there was a short service. Then we went and signed the re
g
ister and - they wished us well and pelted us with confetti as we went and got in the carriage and then that - thing came off as I told you about. Some practical joker, of course there was the usual tying of old boots and all sorts of things on the - on t
he axle of the back of the carriage and - so as to make sure that people knew who you were a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  couple going home, you see, and - some - this practical joker had pulled the pin out that held the shaft that was between the two horses because there was n
o motor cars then, it was just - there were a few motor cars on the road - they were funning about but they were few and far between. And - there was no wedding - carriages - motor carriages - they were horse carriages and there were the pair of horses, t
w
o horses with a shaft in between them to which they were linked. And this shaft was pushed into a socket in the front of the carriage and then there was a lynch pin pushed in to hold it in place so that as the horses went round corners and that sort of th
i
ng - that made it able to follow the horses where it went. Well some demon had pulled that pin out - practically out - thinking no doubt that when the man went to start the carriage away that - the horses would go and leave us behind so as to create a div
ersion. But actually - it - the thing - the horses pulled the carriage away from where we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  and - I think there was about, perhaps a quarter of a mile from the market place through which we had to go at Enfield, quite a large market place, very b
usy on a Saturday afternoon, that was a Saturday afternoon when we got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
. And there were swarms of people, hundreds of people in this market looking at the stalls and going on the round about and all that sort of thing - it's quite an occasion, Satur
day market in Enfield Town and as our carriage got to the market - whether it was the horses gave an extra tug or what I don't know, but the they pulled away, see, and dragged the coachman off the - his seat and of course were would have - it would have b
e
en a calamity because they were still not some of their traces fastened to the carriage and they would have - the carriage, not having anything to guide it would have have gone wobble - wobble all over the place and - well it would have caused casualties 
i
n the crowds that we were going through, walking all over the roads as well as in the market you see, that - caused quite a sensation. Fortunately there was a quick witted - quick witted man in the crowd who - and another one came to help him and they gra
b
bed the horses before they got up any speed at running away and - of course then the carriage stopped and the coal man picked himself up off the road and started getting the horses back into - with the pole into position so as he could go away again. And 
w
hile that was going on of course the ordered were milling round saying, -oh let's have a look at - let's have a look at the bride. And of course my poor wife was subjected to all kinds of remarks and - plenty of jokes and whatnot. With the crowds milling 
round the carriage. However they got the pole back in the carriage and back we went.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have a white wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have plenty of presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about the guests - did you just have the families or friends as well?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, just friends - friends. Wife's friends and some of ours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. No, we couldn't have - I couldn't have any holidays. All I could have was - I had a Saturday - it was August Bank Holiday Saturday, I 
had a Saturday off and I had a Bank Holiday Monday off. I was supposed to go in on Tuesday but I didn't go in but I had to lose the money for that. Didn't get paid for that. But I kept the Tuesday off so I had Monday and Tuesday to - start digging in the 
garden actually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you live in Edmonton after you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No - Enfield.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Sixteen years I think it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So it would be after the end of 1918 before you moved?
