\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes. Yes, we'd 
got - hadn't got any special friends that - that the others didn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 About how often would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well they were welcome to come in at any time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink when they came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes. Cup of tea or some - stay to tea or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were they invited on any particular days or occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Not that I can know of except - well then of course even then our friends weren't so m
uch - as our - they - they were not at our disposal because - our Christmas was spent at our parents home you see and so - the - that - our friends were - some of our friends were there 'cos they were equally friends of theirs. They were mostly relations 
that used to gather round at Christmas time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 You say that friends invited into the home were friends of both of you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 They called in any time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 That's right, yes, they were always welcome.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about neighbours - did they call in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No. No, was like - was a - usual suburban set-up. Our neighbours were friendly but not - very - closely associated you see. We got on very well with ou
r neighbours. Certainly up to 1918, that - the neighbours were very friendly that - we talked to and the old lady next door one way, my wife used to set to and clean her doorstep for her because she thought that she could do it when she did her own doorst
e
p she did the old lady's next door so - you see they were on a fairly friendly footing that is of course, they were ready to do a good turn if there was a good turn wanted the same as - well it was a kind of a friendly set up but - they weren't involved i
n any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 They weren't continually popping in and out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No - they weren't involved in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh I suppose so. In the limited time that was at our disposal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 People often tell us
 that in those days they made their own amusements - what did you do when you got together with friends or neighbours - did you make music or play games of any sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well the only time that we got together was as I say at weekends and then we used to
 play music and sing hymns, as I think I told you before, there was a regular gang used to gather round at me father's place and - on the week - at the weekend on the Sunday and sing and play and there was real orchestra there - unofficial.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh no, we bought the place. We had a mortgage on it which we paid off gradually. You know, the usual regular payments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
In the district where you lived then who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh couldn't tell you - d
on't think anybody was thought to be very important. You know, not super important. No, not that I know of. I don't know of anybody there that was thought of very specially.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Not the ministers of the churches or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Well - wel
l we didn't reckon he was anybody important of course there was the - the church at the end of our road and the ministers there used to visit houses and I suppose the people used to regard him as a - man that was interested in their welfare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you tell me who the shopkeepers associated with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, I didn't know them very well. - They were - they - who they associated with I couldn't tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about the clergy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 As I - well I say there was a vicar and how far he - associated with th
e people I couldn't say because I knew him as the vicar and saw him about and - you know, he say good morning to you and all that sort of thing but - never had much to do with the church or church people. Never went to the church at all. And the shopkeepe
rs well, they were just ordinary people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well I didn't know any of the teachers there. But I guess they were just ordinary people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Farmers - were there any farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, there were one or two farmers but the - there
 were no farms close to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Who would the employers have mixed with socially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
I should imagine with their own - with their - with the employers class so to speak. Except of course in private life they were just ordinary people. If you - speak of
 the - big - commercial - or forget now what estates they call them - where the big factories are - there was a big factory area in Enfield and of course the shop - the factory people that owned the factories, they were large companies you see with huge n
u
mber of share holders and the people that ran them, there was the managing directors and - and such - the people under him. The - chappie that looked after the clerical side of the work. For instance the factory where I worked you see there was - over two
 
thousand people employed, most of them women. And there were the - there was very nearly as many - on the managing side of the business as what there was - out of that two thousand there was very nearly - well, I suppose I'm wrong in saying there was near
l
y as many - there was a tremendous number on the - clerical side. Sort of passengers, they weren't making anything. Weren't doing anything as particularly useful except - making sure that the people that did do the work was not dodging it. See there was a
 
- quite a number of people employed on making sure that went on because they got some kind of scheme they worked on - there was a certain number of them used to go round the works with a stop watch in one hand and a - tablet in the other hand to write on 
s
eeing how many things per minute were turned out on all the operations, it was all - mass production, you see, two girls turning out things which were quick to do could keep six girls going on a - slower operation and they was all schemed out like that. W
e
ll there was a - a - a department of about - oh I should think ten people under a boss - scheming out how many girls - if - all the different things which were manufactured, how long it would take these various operations to be required drilling, making t
h
e screw, threads in them, making the screws on them. How many the automatic - they knew how many the automatic machines could turn out where you put a great long rod of metal in to the machine and that shot a little bit out - brought up a tool to turn it 
d
own to a certain diameter, the tool went back and another one came forward and put a screw thread on it and then that went out of the way and the metal went a little bit further out of the chuck and another tool come up and cut it off. It fell in a little
 
cup and it went round and was picked up again and a - a little saw went it across it and cut a slot in it so it was screw and then it dropped in a - a little egg cup with a tail hanging on it, went round and it tipped up and fell in a tray at the bottom w
h
ere somebody come along and collected 'em in thousands. You see, that was the kind of thing that went on and this particular department, they knew how long it took to do all these operations you see, and they worked it all out. It takes six girls working 
w
ith two girls there and then three there, four more and so on all along until they got a whole - room at work making a certain thing, say a meter. All the various different parts, screws, some of 'em with a - made out of a quarter inch material others of 
t
hem perhaps - well they were only a hundredth of an inch in diameter and so many - some with - ten threads to the inch and others with - a hundred threads to the inch. See - or more than that. You know, turning all these things out. Well then all those pe
o
ple were there - they weren't ; you might say they weren't doing anything as far as making the things was concerned but their wages had got to be paid. Then there was these fellows with the tablet and stop watch used to go round - paid wages but they were
n
't doing anything for - for anybody. They were just checking on - see whether the - the six girls that was turning out the work whether they couldn't get five girls to do that work by working a little quicker and they'd say that instead of you picking up 
t
hat thing with your left hand and - putting it on and then picking it up with the right hand to pass it to the girls next door, you pick it up with your right hand to pass it to the girl next door, you pick it up with your right hand to start with and you
'
ll save - instead of doing fifty - fifty per minute you'll do sixty and then you see we - we can do without one of you girls - five of you can do it if you all do it that way, see. So - seeing where they could cut down the price - the cost of manufacture 
y
ou see. So that you got a tremendous staff there doing nothing but - sort of watching other people work. Yes, that's right, time and motion study. So that - very difficult to say. You see, the - the - to say what class those people belonged to I couldn't 
say. It's entirely impersonal and that - course what was being done in our place was - duplicated all over the shop. We had two thousand people but there's some factories had got ten thousand working there - they go in and out of the gates every day.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
What sort of people would you say went to the church and what sort to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well they - equally divided as far as I know. In our meeting place we had various people as I said - I think I told you before, we had a doctor, we had a chemist. We ha
d a banker and - well all kinds - all kinds - all walks of life. One chappie was a - decorator working for a - an Oxford Street firm that were doing decorations in homes of the wealthy and - a kind - a very super kind of workman. But on the other hand the
r
e was just a - ordinary painter. So that there were all kinds of people used to come there and I - I expect that was duplicated in all the churches. All seemed to be very much about the same. They made an appeal to everybody and everyone that felt the - u
rge, that felt the call and obeyed went and - went there. So that I don't think there was any - there was across section of humanity went to all the different places of worship I should say. Don't think it was confined to any one class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Where you lived
 did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh no, they weren't the same standard of living. It was pretty obvious you see, there were no - social security then and if you wa
s out of work you didn't get any pay. And if you was in a job where the guv'nor could get another - another - man to take your place by lifting up his hand you didn't very - he wasn't very particular about giving you the sack, if you didn't please him you
 
see. - So for perhaps - I was going to say, even for looking across the street - watching somebody go by - would get you the sack. When I first went to work - 'cos it was later - it was after 1918 when I went to work at this place where all these two thou
s
and people were - if a - I know where - I should think twelve girls worked on that particular section. Twelve girls got the sack but - you know, had to go down the Labour Exchange and put their names down to be - for a job. Just because a girl came in lat
e
 - she knew she'd be stopped a quarter of an hour because she was five minutes late see they'd stop her a quarter of an hours pay. The consequence is she thought she'd got ten minutes of her own, you see, as she'd got to lose the money for it. She went an
d
 sat down at her - place at the bench and took out her - her little old bag and got out her lipstick and was doing her lips with the lipstick and the foreman came up and said - you go and get your cards. Why? I've got ten minutes. No you haven't you came 
i
n late, that was your fault, you lose quarter of an hours pay but not allowed to do that. So you can just go and get your cards. And the other girls on the same bench you see that, the other ten or so girls that was working on the same - particular job, t
h
ey said, oh dad - that's what they used to call the foreman, oh dad, you know, oh shame. Well you can all go. And he fired the lot. Just like that. And that took place all - you know, all through the factory. The girls were absolutely - worth dirt so to s
p
eak. Well he'd only got to ring up - all he'd got to do - they had to do down into the - the Labour Office at the gate - at the gate there was a little office where the employees used to have to be taken on and where they had to leave - get their cards as
 
they call it, they had to go down there and get their cards and the foreman just rang up that - the - the foreman just rang up that little office and say well I - I've got six more girls or twelve more girls - get me another twelve girls and in a quarter 
o
f an hour or so there'd be some girls put - coming in from outside and offering to take the job. And then they would have to - put their hands of a sheet of - of bright metal and if they left a mark they'd say, oh you won't do. Because you see they were h
a
ndling things and - metal things and if any perspiring hands would spoil the things you see when they were assembled. Yes, you see, the things were assembled as they went along the line, if someone with sweaty hands had handled 'em you see they'd be - spo
i
lt - you know rust or - rust marks on 'em or spots of verdigris on you see so they were very, very careful about all that you see. Oh and they had all sorts of checks on them when they came and of course they - if they were taken on they went straight dow
n
 and the new girls was put to work side by side with the girls that was used to the job until she - and they'd gradually shift her about until she was able to be put anywhere on the particular - line to - so that - where they got six girls working to keep
 
two running the next job they'd put her on perhaps they'd have - it'd take three girls to keep three girls doing it so they'd have to take over a different job. But gradually they'd get used to doing all the things that was concerned with that particular 
p
art of the work, making particular part of meter or - time keeper of something of that you see so that - then they were of course they were recognised as valuable when they were good workers and quick and respectable you see and didn't give any trouble. T
h
en perhaps they'd stand a better chance. They wouldn't get the sack quite so quickly. But they were - you know, they'd got no rights. And it - it's very difficult to envisage what it meant to be a single girl in those days. If - if for instance they had g
o
t no parents, couldn't live at home and they'd got to live in lodgings - well, in a place like that where there's a lot of industry there's a good demand for lodgings and you've got to pay a good high price for it. And most of the girls money - when she d
r
aws her money at the end of the week - most of it goes in rent. And then she's got to buy clothes, she's got to look respectable and they were some of them had a very hard time of it - hard thing to do with it. That's at the bottom of a lot of mischief. B
e
cause a girl said to me once, you know I was - I had to visit various departments - sometimes on - for business reasons, you know, go - getting parts and that kind of thing and getting to see what was being done and all that sort of thing and - but - so I
 
could pass the time of day with this girl and something or other cropped up in the course of conversation and she said, well I shall have to get friendly with a soldier soon, she said, I can't live. See get a soldier to go out with and take money off 'em,
 
go in the pubs with 'em. It was really dreadful really. The pressure - the pressure that they work under if they're unfortunate enough to have to depend on their own - efforts. Course nowadays I suppose it's much better because they - if they're out of wo
rk there's money coming in, you see, that they're - at that time if they got the sack well there was no money.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Can you describe families with different standards of living within the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Well of course the - up to 1918 - a lot of peop
le getting very low wages and consequently their standard of living would be much less than somebody who was getting a pound a week more. See the skilled workman who could make things, he was earning fairly good money and got a good standard of life - liv
i
ng. He could afford to buy good food and live in a fairly respectable district. But if he was on the lower rate and perhaps out of work one week in ten he - he - he'd - it was a very different story. Of course his living conditions, he had to live in a pa
r
t of a house perhaps, two or three rooms and - live on much less food and lower quality and his clothing had to wear a lot longer. So that you'd find a man that had got different coloured feet on his socks to the tops because his wife had had to mend up h
is socks with - unravelled another - a pair of old ones that was a different colour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you think that one group felt itself superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well only in that respect that they felt that they were better off because they were better qualified to earn a living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Were some families thought of as rough and some as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes. You might find two houses one next door to the other. One would be the mother and father was in the pub every night and - the - consequently the standar
d of living was much lower and the language was - less respectable and the children uncared for and let run wild. You - you'd find quite a different class. Lot of difference between them. And of course - the people with lower incomes tended to drift into 
t
he same areas, you know, into a certain area and when they got in that certain area all that - their surroundings were of a different standard - much lower standard and it of course became rough. So that there was a St Mary's Road near where we lived that
 
was a home of - sneak thieves and prostitutes that used to haunt the pubs and - all - terrible place where all the - back gardens were common, that's to say there was a place through the fence between the houses all the way along. And if the police were a
f
ter somebody and he dashed into one house he might come out anywhere further down the road or he might even go doggo under the bed upstairs in that house so that - and it was such a state that no policeman dare go down alone. He had to have soon - a pal. 
Always two policemen went together down there and it was a rough you know sort of place and everybody, if they gave an address in St Mary's Road well - knew what sort of people they would be.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Well, yes, for that reason that usually the labourer was a - a - quite - got a very temporary sort of footing because his job might finish at any time in the day - the same day even, but the craftsman, he'd got certain standing and i
f he was a good craftsman he - he - they'd be loath to let him go. And therefore his job was - regular. And he would think of the labourer as being someone who didn't matter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 When you were first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  did you have a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, I - no - no particular struggle. We didn't have - we never had too mucy 'cos of course we'd got the - mortgage to pay which took a good slice out of the - my wages and of course we'd got to live. And we were trying - we were trying to add to our home 
what few things that - we thought we'd like besides what we'd got. We bought most of the furniture that we needed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What difference did it make if you were ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No, I was never out of work and - any illnesses didn't last very long.
 I only had a - day or two off for something - I don't ever remember much of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did you get paid if you had a couple of days off sick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. Oh no, you only got paid if you were there and doing your work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 So you would never have had to get
 help from the Guardians or the Parish or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
No, I don't know what - 1918 - or after 1918 when came about the - out of work pay and help if you were in difficulties I don't know but certainly 1918 I don't think there was anything ava
ilable. I - when my children were born we got - a free doctor's attendance and thirty shillings. Oh no, it wasn't free doctor's attendance. We got thirty shillings - grant of thirty shillings when they were born. That was all. See you had to belong to an 
i
nsurance - thing, I forget when that came in but that was in - the Insurance Act was in - in operation and you got thirty shillings maternity benefit. And - it was pay to - say you got a pension of ten shillings a week I think. And that was to pay a pensi
o
ner ten shillings a week. I don't think there was any other benefits. There may have been out of work benefits but what they were must have been very, very small if there was any. 'Cos if they thought you could live on ten shillings a week - they wouldn't
 
- they'd think you ought to have more incentive to go and get another - job if you were out of work - I don't know what the conditions were 'cos I never had to try it out - but I know I - that we were given thirty shillings each time when the babies were 
born. So we weren't much in pocket over that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Can you tell me about the brother next to you - what was his first job and then his subsequent jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes, well his first job was the one that he stuck to all along. He was apprenticed to printing and 
became a compositor, you know, setting up type. And he struck to that all his life and eventually he became a manager of a whole department of - the reading department, checking on the print for a very large publishing firm, it now operates I think as the
 
Sun Printers at Watford I think their place is - their headquarters. And his son is there and he's a designer of - for all the advertisements that go in books like Country Life and such papers as that. That's to say he sets out the advertisements for peop
l
e that want the advertisements displayed sent in to the firm and it's - all the particulars are given to him and he puts some in large type, some in small and illustrations that they want - taking up a certain amount of - space you see because they say, w
e
ll I want my advertisement in - put in your paper and I can only afford to pay for a quarter of a page or I can pay for half a page you see because they have to pay according to the space they used. And he fits these advertisements in to show to the best 
a
dvantage you see - that's his job, that's what he's doing. It's pretty well paid for. But my brother he got - became a printer. That is to say a compositor to start with which - and of course he - by - hard work and qualities he possessed he got up in the
 straights and he got a good responsible position.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 How about your second brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
My second brother, he went to work - in - on the railway. The Great Centreal Railway. He went there as a clerk in the - office, the accounts office you know, where
 they tot up all the money that's paid in by the booking - the booking offices and all that sort of thing and by the goods - the people that the goods - have their goods carried by - he was in the accounts office there and the railway company offered the 
s
cheme that any of their employees that would take the trouble to - go to college and take a degree in accountancy and things like that - management, they would give them a top job. And he went in for it and qualified. He got a B.A. degree and - then he - 
h
e got very - uneasy in his - his outlook and sort of rebellious against authority and chucked up his job in the end and emigrated and went out to Canada and took up a plot of land from the government to do farming out there. And - of course he spent all h
i
s life out in Canada. And unfortunately he joined up when the 1914-18 war started he joined up and he went - he became a commander or a battalion of machine gun - a battalion - a company of machine gunners you see. And he was in charge of machine gunners 
a
nd had a lot of hair raising escapes and experiences. He was given a military medal for holding up a German advance all on his own. The Germans blew up a - you know, made an assault, blow up the trenches and - a bit further along the line from where they 
w
ere and made an advance at the same time to follow up the advantage, I think it - I'm not sure what - whether it was the Suffolk regiment, anyhow it was some regiment were falling back in front of the Germans and he went out to them and sort of rallied 'e
m
 round to come and bring up ammunition for him and went out all alone in more or less the open where - but fortunately the Germans hadn't got his position pinpointed as they'd got all the planes pinpointed so their artillery could drop shells on any point
,
 see if one at the - if one of the forward officers in the forward line - wirelessed back to say I want a barrage on number six square, see, or six B - on six B. He'd look on his map, 6B, oh certain - certain angle, certain elevation see put his guns and 
t
hen few seconds there was falling down - tons of shells falling on that square you see. But fortunately for my brother - he - he went to point where they hadn't got it pin-pointed so there was nobody able to say where he was to get up near the artillery f
i
re but he was exposed to machine gun fire and - rifle fire and help up the Gerry advance because you see you can't advance against a machine gun that's firing because you've got ten bullets a second flying out of the - out of the barrel of the gun and it'
s
 going like this you see, just about the level of your tummy and of course, you - you know, the people that - anyone tried to advance automatically they'd just fall down. Held 'em up just long enough so that the commander of that particular section could 
g
et his men together and come back again and hold up the Gerries that were trying to advance - that would have advanced and taken over their trenches you see and bin quarter of a mile perhaps further in you see. He was given the military medal for that but
 
later on when the British started to advance he was in with the advance troops and he took his battalion out ahead and they were gassed. And - he was badly gassed and he was wounded - he got shrapnel, bullets went through his shoulder and so he was really
 
crippled up. Well he came back - he was in hospital in - France and then sent back to England and recovered to a certain extent so that he was able to go down to Seaford where they were training the new recruits and take over training the machine gunners,
 
you know, teaching them how to set up a box barrage or a - in circles or a square block with bullets every nine inches all the time see, that's what they - they'd been doing. Bullet every time - bullet all the time every nine inches because when one gun w
a
s putting on a fresh belt there was somebody else taking up you see and doing the same business you see going - you got so many degrees of a circle to - move his gun all the time, see and such an elevation he was just - given orders and that was his job, 
t
o keep bullets flying all over so it was impossible to do anything against it. And he - he had the job of training these chappies. But - and he went back to Canada and started farming again but he was gassed - his lungs were so damaged that - it came back
 
on him and about two years after the war was over he died. He got worse and worse and he went to hospital and - then he was transferred to another hospital about - two days journey from where his farm was - the nearest - nearest big town. And he was there
 
for some weeks and finally his wife thought she'd like to go and see him so she made arrangements with the neighbours who were very good - of course their nearest neighbours probably a couple of mile away, being a large cattle farm he was running. She got
 
someone to promise to come and give a hand with the cattle, you know, see they didn't stray away too far and - went in to see him. And so she asked - 'cos he kept writing home and saying that he hoped to be better and he'd be coming home. And she asked th
e
 - official there at the hospital, you know, if he - if he - if it would be any good writing to his - own relations in England and going back to England when he got better. So he said, oh, he said, no if he, you know, when he's better he'd be right fit to
 
- you know - he'd - that'd be as good as anywhere for him to live. He could live in England as good as he could in Canada if he - if he gets over it and, you know, they kept on talking like that then gradually - they began to take it back and let her know
 
that there was no hope for him you see, that it was just a mater of time. And he eventually faded out. And of course she'd got this one boy, little boy that was born, so she went back and - sold up the cattle that they'd got and parted up with the farm an
d
 brought him over here - went back to live with her mother that was still alive and lived with her. Then she came and lived with my mother and father. Brought the little boy and he lived with them. And they lived next door to us so - that's what happened 
to him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 What were your brothers names by the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
My brother that's still alive his name Ernest George and the one that died his name was Wilfred Charles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you tell me about your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Yes, her name was Beatrice Nellie. She was -
 fairly delicate youngster but developed up quite a strong young woman. She was a very good pianist and could play the violin too very well. Don't think she could sing much but she was very much sought after because of her being very personable young woma
n
 and - she went to a training college to learn secretarial work and finally she became the private secretary to the general manager of the Remington typewriter company so you can tell she was a good typewriter. And - that's where she - that was her life w
ork. When she got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
 of course she left her job - they were very sorry to lose her and she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
 a chap who was an engineer at a foundry. Large iron foundry in Bristol. And - she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392  him you see. Unfortunately she died - she got leukemia. So - of
 course it wasn't known as leukemia, I forget now what they called it. But that's what - and of course she - nothing was much good to - she - at times she seemed to rally and be better but - and it took a long time - a passage of years really before she a
ctually died but - she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 And her husband worked as an engineer in a foundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
He was a found - he was a foreman a manager of the foundry - a big printing engineers in - in Bristol. It's renowned all over the world at the present day. He's stil
l alive but he's retired from work for a long time - 'cos he's - he's my age or if anything a little older than I am. He was older than what she was. I had a letter from him this Christmas time. 'Cos while he was in Enfield I had a good bit to do with him
 one way and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 I've forgotten what your wife's job before you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Oh yes, she worked at something to do with a - with the printing of the stamps. At Delarues a place it used - and I don't know whether - I think they still do print stamps for the government. But it was only just an ordinary sort of job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Was she there from when she left school 'til she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 
Yes she went there - went to work there when she left school. Her sister was already working there and so she followed her example - she - she would have liked to have been a nurse but her mother wouldn't stand for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Did she work at all after you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15740825 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3417349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Can you tell me about your daughter and her career?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3421161 DW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14944392\charrsid14944392 Oh - oh yes, well she wen
t to school then she went to the High school, cos she finished her school - she was at high school in Enfield but when we moved down to Clacton she went to the - high school there. And then eventually finding that she she wanted to be a teacher and findin
g
 that to get into college she'd got to get a certain education she found out that the high school wasn't good enough to be certain to - to produce that effect and she went to Colchester to the Colchester High school in Colchester and finished her - school
d
ays there. And passed out - and got a place in the teaching college in - Brighton. And - was it Brighton or Bournemouth? I'll have to ask her. She went to Brighton college and got her qualifications there and got a job at - teaching at Clacton where we we
r
e living. And then she - when my son who was at - had started training to be an accountant - he was articled to an accountants in the Strand and - training and eventually passed the examination and became a chartered accountant. He was - of course had a l
o
t of swotting to do and a two hour journey in the morning going up from Clacton to - London and a two hour journey coming back from London to Clacton after he'd finished a day's work wasn't very good for putting in a lot of arduous study because the exams
 
really are tough and require a lot of work. So eventually we moved - or his mother moved away, I'd got the little shop at Clacton, she moved - to - a place near - nearer London where it was a very short journey on the Met. - on an underground railway. She
 
went to Upminster. Well that - then Elsie left the school at Clacton and went to a school at - Harold Wood. And then finding that teachers salaries in Harold Wood were very much below the salaries in the London area she - went after some, you know, or put
 
in an application for - for a job in Enfield where some of our relations lived - and - got a job in one of the Enfield schools and then - her mother - moved and we took the - up a mortgage on a house - a newly - new estate - building estate that was being
 
built near Enfield Town station and - they went and lived over there. So Elsie was teaching in Enfield at a - what you call a Secondary Modern School. And she kept that job until we came down here to live and when we came down here to live and her mother 
w
as so ill 'cos she was ill for two years, quite - unable to help herself for two years and for the last eight months unable to move out of bed or anything and had to have everything - everything had to be done for her. So it was necessary for two people t
o
 be there day and night. So - see her sister living here in Mersea she was able to come round all day and - it rell on Elsie to be here and he on hand all night. And so she was called on two or three times to get up during the night to come and lend a han
d
 because - it took two people to handle her and sometime it was as much as three times in the night that she had to be handles and dealt with so - and of course that was getting too much for Elsie and - well she had to do that and that's why she came to l
i
ve - or came to a school where she could get - home fairly early so as to be on hand to lend a hand. Until it got as bad as that we had to do without - that's how we managed. But when it got as bad as that we had to have the - official - health service nu
r
se who would come in and - come in at nine o'clock at night and stay 'til eight o'clock the next morning - so Elsie was able to get a nights sleep in. But - the nearest place she could get to the school was any good was - a place called Wetherden and she 
